{"title_page": "Climate change in the Caribbean", "text_new": "[[Human impact on the environment|Anthropogenic]] climate change is caused by the rapid increase of [[greenhouse gases]] in the [[atmosphere]] principally from burning [[fossil fuels]], converting forestland to [[pasture]] and [[monoculture]] cropland, with the greatest contributions happening in the period since the [[Industrial Revolution]]. [[File:Karte Karibik Inseln.png|thumb|right|Map of the Caribbean|427x427px]]\n'''[[Climate change]]''' could pose disadvantageous risks to the islands in the '''[[Caribbean]]'''.<ref name=book2016>{{cite book|editor1-last=Clinton L. Beckford |editor2= Kevon Rhiney|title=Globalization, Agriculture and Food in the Caribbean|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn= 978-1-137-53837-6|chapter=1|doi= 10.1057/978-1-137-53837-6|year= 2016}}</ref> The environmental changes expected to affect the Caribbean are a rise in sea level, stronger hurricanes, longer dry seasons and shorter wet seasons.<ref name=\"book2016\" /><ref name=\"Jackson2016\">{{cite web|url=https://climate.nasa.gov/effects|title=Global Climate Change: Effects|last1=Jackson|first1=Randal}}</ref> As a result, climate change is expected to lead to changes in the economy, environment and population of the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Batiste2016\">{{cite journal|author1=Batiste, April Karen|author2=Rhiney, Kevon|date=July 1, 2016|title=Climate justice and the Caribbean: An introduction|url= |journal=Geoforum|volume=73|issue=Supplement C|pages=17\u201321|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2016.04.008|issn=0016-7185}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/rp/Caribbean-full-Eng.pdf|title=The Caribbean and climate change: The costs of inaction|author1=Ram\u00f3n Bueno|author2=Cornella Herzfeld|author3=Elizabeth A. Stanton|author4=Frank Ackerman|date=May 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore2017\">{{cite journal|author1=Winston Moore|author2=Wayne Elliot|author3=Troy Lorde|date=2017-04-01|title=Climate change, Atlantic storm activity and the regional socio-economic impacts on the Caribbean|journal=Environment, Development and Sustainability|volume=19|issue=2|pages=707\u2013726|doi=10.1007/s10668-016-9763-1|issn=1387-585X}}</ref><ref name=\"Reyer2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Reyer|first1=Christopher|date=2017-08-01|title=Climate change impacts in Latin America and the Caribbean and their implications for development|journal=Regional Environmental Change|volume=17|issue=6|pages=1601\u20131621|doi=10.1007/s10113-015-0854-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sealey-Huggins|first1=Leon|date=2017-11-02|title='1.5\u00b0C to stay alive': climate change, imperialism and justice for the Caribbean|journal=Third World Quarterly|volume=38|issue=11|pages=2444\u20132463|doi=10.1080/01436597.2017.1368013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Caribbean#Geography_and_geology}}\nThe Caribbean is composed of an archipelago of islands between North and South America. These islands are [[Antigua]], [[Aruba]], [[Barbados]], [[Bonaire]], the [[Cayman Islands]], [[Cuba]], [[Curacao]], [[Dominica]], [[Guadeloupe]], [[Grenada]], [[Hispaniola]], [[Jamaica]], [[Martinique]], [[Montserrat]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Saba]], [[Saint Croix]], [[Saint Eustatius]], [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]], [[Saint Kitts]], [[Saint Lucia]], [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Saint Vincent (island)|Saint Vincent]], Sint Maarten, [[the Bahamas]], [[Tortola]], and [[Trinidad and Tobago]].The climate average annual temperature of the Caribbean is 81&nbsp;\u00b0F.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentresults.com/Weather/Caribbean/average-annual-temperature-rainfall.php|title=Caribbean Weather: Annual Temperature & Rainfall - Current Results|website=www.currentresults.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental changes==\n===Rise in sea level===\nRising sea levels are expected to cause [[coastal erosion]] due to climate change. According to NASA, the sea level is expected to increase by {{convert|1|-|4|feet|sigfig=1|order=flip}} by 2100.<ref name=Jackson2016 /> Rise in sea level could impact coastal communities of the Caribbean if they are less than {{convert|10|feet|sigfig=1|order=flip}} above the sea. In Latin America and the Caribbean, it is expected that 29 \u2013 32 million people may be affected by the sea level rise because they live below this threshold. The Bahamas, Trinidad and Tobago are expected to be the most affected because at least 80% of the total land is below the sea level.<ref name=Lewsey2004 >{{cite journal|author1=Clement Lewsey|author2=Gonzalo Cid|author3=Edward Kruse|title=Assessing climate change impacts on coastal infrastructure in the Eastern Caribbean|journal=Marine Policy|date=2004-09-01|volume=28|issue=5|pages=393\u2013409|doi=10.1016/j.marpol.2003.10.016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Borja G. Reguero|author2=I\u00f1igo J. Losada|author3=Pedro D\u00edaz-Simal|author4=Fernando J. M\u00e9ndez|author5=Michael W. Beck|title=Effects of Climate Change on Exposure to Coastal Flooding in Latin America and the Caribbean|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=10|issue=7|page=e0133409|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0133409|pmid=26177285|pmc=4503776|year=2015}}</ref> Coastal losses range between US$940 million to $1.2 billion in the 22 largest coastal cities in Latin America and the Caribbean.<ref name=Reyer2017 /> Main sources of income, such as tourism, will also be affected because many of the main touristic attractions such as beaches and hotels are near the coast. In 2004, a study reported that 12 million tourists had visited the Caribbean. Damage to the beaches can also negatively impact sea turtles that nest in the Caribbeans. The islands are home to a few species of sea turtles, which are all facing endangerment due to the coastal erosion. Sea level rise can impact where sea turtles nest and their nesting behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fish|first=Marianne R.|last2=C\u00f4t\u00e9|first2=Isabelle M.|last3=Gill|first3=Jennifer A.|last4=Jones|first4=Andrew P.|last5=Renshoff|first5=Saskia|last6=Watkinson|first6=Andrew R.|date=2005|title=Predicting the Impact of Sea-Level Rise on Caribbean Sea Turtle Nesting Habitat|journal=Conservation Biology|language=en|volume=19|issue=2|pages=482\u2013491|doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2005.00146.x|issn=1523-1739}}</ref>\n\n===Increased air and sea surface temperature===\n[[File:2017 Atlantic hurricane season summary map.png|thumb|right|Summary map of the 2017 Atlantic hurricane season from NASA|306x306px]]\nAn increase in air and [[sea surface]] temperature is predicted to promote the development of stronger [[Tropical cyclones|tropical cyclone]] (also known as hurricanes). Key factors that lead to the development of hurricanes are the warm temperatures of the air and sea surface. The higher temperatures increase the probability of the storm to become a hurricane. This provides the energy for the hurricane to intensify.<ref name=\"MSCF2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/audience/forstudents/5-8/features/nasa-knows/what-are-hurricanes-58.html|title=What Are Hurricanes?|last1=Wall|first1=Jennifer|website=NASA|date=2015-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Plumer2016\">{{cite web|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=How do hurricanes form? A step-by-step guide|url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2016/10/6/13191010/how-hurricanes-form-tropical-storms-guide|website=Vox|date=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the United States [[National Hurricane Center]] reported that the [[North Atlantic basin tropical cyclone|North Atlantic basin]] was highly active because four [[tropical storms]] formed and they all became hurricanes. They report a higher than average record on the number of tropical storms that developed into hurricanes this year.<ref name=\"MATW\">{{cite web|title=Monthly Atlantic Tropical Weather Summary|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/text/MIATWSAT.shtml}}</ref> Two of these four hurricanes, [[Hurricane Irma|Irma]] and [[Hurricane Maria|Maria]], hit the islands in the Caribbean. Once at the Caribbean, both Irma and Maria became Category 5 hurricanes.<ref name=\"RAIN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2017/9/28/16362522/hurricane-maria-2017-irma-harvey-rain-flooding-climate-change|title=One of the clearest signs of climate change in Hurricanes Maria, Irma, and Harvey was the rain|date=2017-09-28}}</ref> NASA reported that the temperature of the sea surface in the Caribbean when Irma became a hurricane was {{convert|86|F|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"MATW\" /> The required temperature for the development of a major storm is suggested to be higher than {{convert|80|F|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"Plumer2016\" />  [[File:Hurricane Maria (2017) 170923-H-NI589-0002 (37312143081).jpg|thumb|right| Destroyed homes after Hurricane Maria in Puerto Rico|305x305px]]Hurricanes of category 5 have wind speeds greater than 157&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"MSCF2015\" /> In addition to being strong, Hurricanes Irma and Maria also carried more rainfall than previous storms. The warmer the air temperature, the more water can be held by air leading to more [[precipitation]]. Multiple sources suggest that this increase in strengthening and precipitation in recent hurricanes is due to climate change.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Michael|title=Climate change in the Caribbean \u2013 learning lessons from Irma and Maria|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/oct/06/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-learning-lessons-from-irma-and-maria|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2017-10-06}}</ref><ref name=\"RAIN\" /><ref name=\"CCITCMI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iadb.org/en/office-of-evaluation-and-oversight/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-small-island-states,18283.html|title=Climate Change in the Caribbean Small Island States|website=Inter-American Development Bank}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wallace-Wells|first1=David|title=Will Irma Finally Change the Way We Talk About Climate?|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/09/will-irma-finally-change-the-way-we-talk-about-climate.html|website=Daily Intelligencer|accessdate=2017-09-09}}</ref> Hurricane Irma and Maria had a total of {{convert|20|inch|order=flip}} of rainfall. In Cuba, Hurricane Irma sustained precipitation was at {{convert|10.8|inch|order=flip}} per hour. In Puerto Rico, Hurricane Maria had a sustained precipitation of {{convert|6.44|inch|order=flip}} per hour.<ref name=\"RAIN\" /> We are seeing repeated and prolonged droughts, an increase in the number of very hot days, intense rainfall events causing repeated localized flooding, and rising sea levels that are consuming the beautiful beaches on which tourism in the region depends.<ref>Taylor, Michael. https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/oct/06/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-learning-lessons-from-irma-and-maria. \"Climate change in the Caribbean- Learning lessons from Irma and Maria\". 6 October 2017.</ref>\n\nAn increase in surface temperature has also been suggested to affect the [[coral reef]]s. In 2005 in the Caribbean, a rise in the sea surface temperature is thought to have caused widespread coral bleaching. In this study, they evaluate if this increase in sea surface temperature was due to natural climate variability or human activity. They concluded that it would be very unlikely that natural climate variability alone could account for this event. Their model suggests that this event would occur once every 1000 years if human activity is not taken into consideration in the model.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Simon D. Donner|author2=Thomas R. Knutson|title=Model-based assessment of the role of human-induced climate change in the 2005 Caribbean coral bleaching event|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=2007-03-27|volume=104|issue=13|pages=5483\u20135488|doi=10.1073/pnas.0610122104|pmid=17360373|pmc=1838457}}</ref> Coral reefs are a huge part of the Caribbean ocean and an important aspect to their ecosystem. Coral bleaching is an effect of the change in climate because of the rise in water temperature in the seawater. The coral is also being used as a \"natural resource\" for the natives to create cement and aggregate because they aren't provided with the same materials as are other countries.\n\n==Social and economic impacts==\n\nMultiple sources suggest that the Caribbean is in a particularly difficult position to address climate change.<ref name=\"Batiste2016\" /><ref name=\"Reyer2017\" /> The Caribbean's long history of colonialism for the extraction of goods, such as sugar, has left them dependent on colonial entities. This has created a disadvantage to the Caribbean as they lack the ability to compete with the current [[world economy]] and be self-sufficient. Centuries of [[colonialism]] has generated a feedback loop of the dependence of the Caribbean's economy on global powers.<ref name=Batiste2016 />\n\nThe damages expected from climate change will weaken the economy of the Caribbean as it will target some of the major sources of income, like tourism. It has been estimated that 25% to 35% of the Caribbean's economy relies on tourism.<ref name=\"Lewsey2004\" /> Tourism could be significantly reduced if less tourists travel to the Caribbean because of an increase in the strength and likelihood of hurricanes in the next century. It is expected that hurricane costs are expected to range between US$350 to $550 million or about 11% to 17% of the current [[GDP]] for hurricane damages annually. They expect that the Bahamas, Haiti, and Jamaica are the islands that will suffer the most from climate change. In addition, they suggest that agricultural and rural areas are among the sectors that will be most affected by hurricanes in the Caribbean. They estimate that damages to these areas could cost about US$3 million per year by 2050 and US$12 \u2013 $15 million by 2100.<ref name=\"Reyer2017\" />\n\n== Cultural Impacts ==\nThere are a variety of people that live on the Caribbean islands and they are heavily impacted on the effects of climate change. Culturally, the peoples of the Caribbean are a mix of Africa, Asian, European, and Indigenous peoples.<ref>Coastal Education & Research. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25736087?seq=5#metadata_info_tab_contents. \"Climate change impacts on the Caribbean coastal areas and tourism\". ISSUE NO. 24. pp. 49-69.</ref> [[Tourism]] is an important aspect in the Caribbeans economy. Without it economies will collapse and residents will struggle more than they already are. The impact of climate change on tourism will lead to unknown results and many difficulties for the islands. The coastal region, where tourist reside on their trips, is nothing like the original residence for the natives.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Climate change]] (modern day)\n* [[Climate change (general concept)]]\n* [[Hurricane Irma]]\n* [[Caribbean Sea]]\n* [[Coral bleaching]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}Added Links:\n\n# https://www.jstor.org/stable/41917607?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents CLIMATE CHANGE AND THE CARIBBEAN: REVIEW AND RESPONSE\n# https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/2010EO160002 Volcanic Vents Found in Deep Caribbean Waters\n\n==Further reading== \n* {{cite report|author=U.S. Global Change Research Program|year=2018|chapter=U.S. Caribbean|title=Impacts, Risks, and Adaptation in the United States: Fourth National Climate Assessment, Volume II|publisher=U.S. Global Change Research Program|place=Washington, DC, USA|page=809\u2013871|doi=10.7930/NCA4.2018.CH20|doi-access=free}}\n \n{{Americas topic|Climate change in }}\n[[Category:Geography of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Regional effects of global warming]]\n[[Category:Climate change]]\n[[Category:Climate change articles needing expert attention]]\n", "text_old": "[[Human impact on the environment|Anthropogenic]] climate change is caused by the rapid increase of [[greenhouse gases]] in the [[atmosphere]] principally from burning [[fossil fuels]], converting forestland to [[pasture]] and [[monoculture]] cropland, with the greatest contributions happening in the period since the [[Industrial Revolution]]. [[File:Karte Karibik Inseln.png|thumb|right|Map of the Caribbean|427x427px]]\n'''[[Climate change]]''' could pose disadvantageous risks to the islands in the '''[[Caribbean]]'''.<ref name=book2016>{{cite book|editor1-last=Clinton L. Beckford |editor2= Kevon Rhiney|title=Globalization, Agriculture and Food in the Caribbean|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn= 978-1-137-53837-6|chapter=1|doi= 10.1057/978-1-137-53837-6|year= 2016}}</ref> The environmental changes expected to affect the Caribbean are a rise in sea level, stronger hurricanes, longer dry seasons and shorter wet seasons.<ref name=\"book2016\" /><ref name=\"Jackson2016\">{{cite web|url=https://climate.nasa.gov/effects|title=Global Climate Change: Effects|last1=Jackson|first1=Randal}}</ref> As a result, climate change is expected to lead to changes in the economy, environment and population of the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Batiste2016\">{{cite journal|author1=Batiste, April Karen|author2=Rhiney, Kevon|date=July 1, 2016|title=Climate justice and the Caribbean: An introduction|url= |journal=Geoforum|volume=73|issue=Supplement C|pages=17\u201321|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2016.04.008|issn=0016-7185}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/rp/Caribbean-full-Eng.pdf|title=The Caribbean and climate change: The costs of inaction|author1=Ram\u00f3n Bueno|author2=Cornella Herzfeld|author3=Elizabeth A. Stanton|author4=Frank Ackerman|date=May 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore2017\">{{cite journal|author1=Winston Moore|author2=Wayne Elliot|author3=Troy Lorde|date=2017-04-01|title=Climate change, Atlantic storm activity and the regional socio-economic impacts on the Caribbean|journal=Environment, Development and Sustainability|volume=19|issue=2|pages=707\u2013726|doi=10.1007/s10668-016-9763-1|issn=1387-585X}}</ref><ref name=\"Reyer2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Reyer|first1=Christopher|date=2017-08-01|title=Climate change impacts in Latin America and the Caribbean and their implications for development|journal=Regional Environmental Change|volume=17|issue=6|pages=1601\u20131621|doi=10.1007/s10113-015-0854-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sealey-Huggins|first1=Leon|date=2017-11-02|title='1.5\u00b0C to stay alive': climate change, imperialism and justice for the Caribbean|journal=Third World Quarterly|volume=38|issue=11|pages=2444\u20132463|doi=10.1080/01436597.2017.1368013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Caribbean#Geography_and_geology}}\nThe Caribbean is composed of an archipelago of islands between North and South America. These islands are [[Antigua]], [[Aruba]], [[Barbados]], [[Bonaire]], the [[Cayman Islands]], [[Cuba]], [[Curacao]], [[Dominica]], [[Guadeloupe]], [[Grenada]], [[Hispaniola]], [[Jamaica]], [[Martinique]], [[Montserrat]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Saba]], [[Saint Croix]], [[Saint Eustatius]], [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]], [[Saint Kitts]], [[Saint Lucia]], [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Saint Vincent (island)|Saint Vincent]], Sint Maarten, [[the Bahamas]], [[Tortola]], and [[Trinidad and Tobago]].The climate average annual temperature of the Caribbean is 81&nbsp;\u00b0F.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentresults.com/Weather/Caribbean/average-annual-temperature-rainfall.php|title=Caribbean Weather: Annual Temperature & Rainfall - Current Results|website=www.currentresults.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental changes==\n===Rise in sea level===\nRising sea levels are expected to cause [[coastal erosion]] due to climate change. According to NASA, the sea level is expected to increase by {{convert|1|-|4|feet|sigfig=1|order=flip}} by 2100.<ref name=Jackson2016 /> Rise in sea level could impact coastal communities of the Caribbean if they are less than {{convert|10|feet|sigfig=1|order=flip}} above the sea. In Latin America and the Caribbean, it is expected that 29 \u2013 32 million people may be affected by the sea level rise because they live below this threshold. The Bahamas, Trinidad and Tobago are expected to be the most affected because at least 80% of the total land is below the sea level.<ref name=Lewsey2004 >{{cite journal|author1=Clement Lewsey|author2=Gonzalo Cid|author3=Edward Kruse|title=Assessing climate change impacts on coastal infrastructure in the Eastern Caribbean|journal=Marine Policy|date=2004-09-01|volume=28|issue=5|pages=393\u2013409|doi=10.1016/j.marpol.2003.10.016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Borja G. Reguero|author2=I\u00f1igo J. Losada|author3=Pedro D\u00edaz-Simal|author4=Fernando J. M\u00e9ndez|author5=Michael W. Beck|title=Effects of Climate Change on Exposure to Coastal Flooding in Latin America and the Caribbean|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=10|issue=7|page=e0133409|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0133409|pmid=26177285|pmc=4503776|year=2015}}</ref> Coastal losses range between US$940 million to $1.2 billion in the 22 largest coastal cities in Latin America and the Caribbean.<ref name=Reyer2017 /> Main sources of income, such as tourism, will also be affected because many of the main touristic attractions such as beaches and hotels are near the coast. In 2004, a study reported that 12 million tourists had visited the Caribbean. Damage to the beaches can also negatively impact sea turtles that nest in the Caribbeans. The islands are home to a few species of sea turtles, which are all facing endangerment due to the coastal erosion. Sea level rise can impact where sea turtles nest and their nesting behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fish|first=Marianne R.|last2=C\u00f4t\u00e9|first2=Isabelle M.|last3=Gill|first3=Jennifer A.|last4=Jones|first4=Andrew P.|last5=Renshoff|first5=Saskia|last6=Watkinson|first6=Andrew R.|date=2005|title=Predicting the Impact of Sea-Level Rise on Caribbean Sea Turtle Nesting Habitat|journal=Conservation Biology|language=en|volume=19|issue=2|pages=482\u2013491|doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2005.00146.x|issn=1523-1739}}</ref>\n\n===Increased air and sea surface temperature===\n[[File:2017 Atlantic hurricane season summary map.png|thumb|right|Summary map of the 2017 Atlantic hurricane season from NASA|306x306px]]\nAn increase in air and [[sea surface]] temperature is predicted to promote the development of stronger [[Tropical cyclones|tropical cyclone]] (also known as hurricanes). Key factors that lead to the development of hurricanes are the warm temperatures of the air and sea surface. The higher temperatures increase the probability of the storm to become a hurricane. This provides the energy for the hurricane to intensify.<ref name=\"MSCF2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/audience/forstudents/5-8/features/nasa-knows/what-are-hurricanes-58.html|title=What Are Hurricanes?|last1=Wall|first1=Jennifer|website=NASA|date=2015-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Plumer2016\">{{cite web|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=How do hurricanes form? A step-by-step guide|url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2016/10/6/13191010/how-hurricanes-form-tropical-storms-guide|website=Vox|date=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the United States [[National Hurricane Center]] reported that the [[North Atlantic basin tropical cyclone|North Atlantic basin]] was highly active because four [[tropical storms]] formed and they all became hurricanes. They report a higher than average record on the number of tropical storms that developed into hurricanes this year.<ref name=\"MATW\">{{cite web|title=Monthly Atlantic Tropical Weather Summary|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/text/MIATWSAT.shtml}}</ref> Two of these four hurricanes, [[Hurricane Irma|Irma]] and [[Hurricane Maria|Maria]], hit the islands in the Caribbean. Once at the Caribbean, both Irma and Maria became Category 5 hurricanes.<ref name=\"RAIN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2017/9/28/16362522/hurricane-maria-2017-irma-harvey-rain-flooding-climate-change|title=One of the clearest signs of climate change in Hurricanes Maria, Irma, and Harvey was the rain|date=2017-09-28}}</ref> NASA reported that the temperature of the sea surface in the Caribbean when Irma became a hurricane was {{convert|86|F|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"MATW\" /> The required temperature for the development of a major storm is suggested to be higher than {{convert|80|F|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"Plumer2016\" />  [[File:Hurricane Maria (2017) 170923-H-NI589-0002 (37312143081).jpg|thumb|right| Destroyed homes after Hurricane Maria in Puerto Rico|305x305px]]Hurricanes of category 5 have wind speeds greater than 157&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"MSCF2015\" /> In addition to being strong, Hurricanes Irma and Maria also carried more rainfall than previous storms. The warmer the air temperature, the more water can be held by air leading to more [[precipitation]]. Multiple sources suggest that this increase in strengthening and precipitation in recent hurricanes is due to climate change.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Michael|title=Climate change in the Caribbean \u2013 learning lessons from Irma and Maria|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/oct/06/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-learning-lessons-from-irma-and-maria|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2017-10-06}}</ref><ref name=\"RAIN\" /><ref name=\"CCITCMI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iadb.org/en/office-of-evaluation-and-oversight/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-small-island-states,18283.html|title=Climate Change in the Caribbean Small Island States|website=Inter-American Development Bank}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wallace-Wells|first1=David|title=Will Irma Finally Change the Way We Talk About Climate?|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/09/will-irma-finally-change-the-way-we-talk-about-climate.html|website=Daily Intelligencer|accessdate=2017-09-09}}</ref> Hurricane Irma and Maria had a total of {{convert|20|inch|order=flip}} of rainfall. In Cuba, Hurricane Irma sustained precipitation was at {{convert|10.8|inch|order=flip}} per hour. In Puerto Rico, Hurricane Maria had a sustained precipitation of {{convert|6.44|inch|order=flip}} per hour.<ref name=\"RAIN\" /> We are seeing repeated and prolonged droughts, an increase in the number of very hot days, intense rainfall events causing repeated localized flooding, and rising sea levels that are consuming the beautiful beaches on which tourism in the region depends.<ref>Taylor, Michael. https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/oct/06/climate-change-in-the-caribbean-learning-lessons-from-irma-and-maria. \"Climate change in the Caribbean- Learning lessons from Irma and Maria\". 6 October 2017.</ref>\n\nAn increase in surface temperature has also been suggested to affect the [[coral reef]]s. In 2005 in the Caribbean, a rise in the sea surface temperature is thought to have caused widespread coral bleaching. In this study, they evaluate if this increase in sea surface temperature was due to natural climate variability or human activity. They concluded that it would be very unlikely that natural climate variability alone could account for this event. Their model suggests that this event would occur once every 1000 years if human activity is not taken into consideration in the model.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Simon D. Donner|author2=Thomas R. Knutson|title=Model-based assessment of the role of human-induced climate change in the 2005 Caribbean coral bleaching event|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=2007-03-27|volume=104|issue=13|pages=5483\u20135488|doi=10.1073/pnas.0610122104|pmid=17360373|pmc=1838457}}</ref> Coral reefs are a huge part of the Caribbean ocean and an important aspect to their ecosystem. Coral bleaching is an effect of the change in climate because of the rise in water temperature in the seawater. The coral is also being used as a \"natural resource\" for the natives to create cement and aggregate because they aren't provided with the same materials as are other countries.\n\n==Social and economic impacts==\n\nMultiple sources suggest that the Caribbean is in a particularly difficult position to address climate change.<ref name=\"Batiste2016\" /><ref name=\"Reyer2017\" /> The Caribbean's long history of colonialism for the extraction of goods, such as sugar, has left them dependent on colonial entities. This has created a disadvantage to the Caribbean as they lack the ability to compete with the current [[world economy]] and be self-sufficient. Centuries of [[colonialism]] has generated a feedback loop of the dependence of the Caribbean's economy on global powers.<ref name=Batiste2016 />\n\nThe damages expected from climate change will weaken the economy of the Caribbean as it will target some of the major sources of income, like tourism. It has been estimated that 25% to 35% of the Caribbean's economy relies on tourism.<ref name=\"Lewsey2004\" /> Tourism could be significantly reduced if less tourists travel to the Caribbean because of an increase in the strength and likelihood of hurricanes in the next century. It is expected that hurricane costs are expected to range between US$350 to $550 million or about 11% to 17% of the current [[GDP]] for hurricane damages annually. They expect that the Bahamas, Haiti, and Jamaica are the islands that will suffer the most from climate change. In addition, they suggest that agricultural and rural areas are among the sectors that will be most affected by hurricanes in the Caribbean. They estimate that damages to these areas could cost about US$3 million per year by 2050 and US$12 \u2013 $15 million by 2100.<ref name=\"Reyer2017\" />\n\n== Cultural Impacts ==\nThere are a variety of people that live on the Caribbean islands and they are heavily impacted on the effects of climate change. Culturally, the peoples of the Caribbean are a mix of Africa, Asian, European, and Indigenous peoples.<ref>Coastal Education & Research. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25736087?seq=5#metadata_info_tab_contents. \"Climate change impacts on the Caribbean coastal areas and tourism\". ISSUE NO. 24. pp. 49-69.</ref> [[Tourism]] is an important aspect in the Caribbeans economy. Without it economies will collapse and residents will struggle more than they already are. The impact of climate change on tourism will lead to unknown results and many difficulties for the islands. The coastal region, where tourist reside on their trips, is nothing like the original residence for the natives.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Climate change]] (modern day)\n* [[Climate change (general concept)]]\n* [[Hurricane Irma]]\n* [[Caribbean Sea]]\n* [[Coral bleaching]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}Added Links:\n\n# https://www.jstor.org/stable/41917607?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents CLIMATE CHANGE AND THE CARIBBEAN: REVIEW AND RESPONSE\n# https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/2010EO160002 Volcanic Vents Found in Deep Caribbean Waters\n\n==Further reading== \n* {{cite report|author=U.S. Global Change Research Program|year=2018|chapter=U.S. Caribbean|title=Impacts, Risks, and Adaptation in the United States: Fourth National Climate Assessment, Volume II|publisher=U.S. Global Change Research Program|place=Washington, DC, USA|page=809\u2013871|doi=10.7930/NCA4.2018.CH20|doi-access=free}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Regional effects of global warming]]\n[[Category:Climate change]]\n[[Category:Climate change articles needing expert attention]]\n", "name_user": "CaribDigita", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change_in_the_Caribbean"}
{"title_page": "Tavistock College", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Tavistock College\n | image                   = Cresttavcoll.jpg\n | image_size              = 150\n | motto                   = Together: we care, we challenge, we excel\n | established             = 1552\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Foundation school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | president               = \n | head_label              = Principal\n | head                    = Sarah Jones<ref>[http://tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/ Tavistock College web site.] Retrieved September 18, 2015.</ref>\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = Chair\n | chair                   = Mandy Govier\n | founder                 = \n | address                 = Crowndale Rd\n | city                    = [[Tavistock, Devon|Tavistock]]\n | county                  = [[Devon]]\n | country                 = [[England]]\n | postcode                = PL19 8DD\n | local_authority         = [[Devon County Council|Devon]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | dfeno                   = \n | urn                     = 113539\n | staff                   = 300\n | enrolment               = approx. 1800\n | gender                  = [[Coeducational]]\n | lower_age               = 11\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = {{color box|#FF0000}} Bedford \n{{color box|#008000}} Drake\n\n{{color box|#800080}} Fitzford\n\n{{color box|#FFFF00}} Glanville\n\n{{color box|#0000FF}} Tremayne\n | colours                 = \n | publication             = In Focus\n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://www.tavistockcollege.org\n}}\n\n'''Tavistock College''' is a mixed gender [[state school|state-funded]] in [[Tavistock, Devon|Tavistock]], [[Devon]], England, with students aged 11\u201318. There were (as of April 2020) approximately 1800 students attending. The schools draws students from a catchment area of about {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} radius.\n\nThe college has links with Japan, [[Uganda]], Spain, Swaziland, Peru, France and India where staff exchanges and student visits and projects take place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/college/|title=The College|publisher=Tavistock College|work=Tavistock College website|accessdate=2007-06-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610041642/http://www.tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/college/|archivedate=2007-06-10}}</ref>\n==Ofsted Reviews==\nIn early 2010, the school received a \"notice to improve\" from [[Ofsted]], the national school inspection agency.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.tavistock-today.co.uk/article.cfm?id=461&headline=Ofsted%20tells%20college%20it%20must%20improve&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2009 | title=Ofsted tells college it must improve |date= 12 February 2009| newspaper =Tavistock Today|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> After a failure to improve, the following year Tavistock College was placed under special measures. \nThe school was placed into special measures in September 2011 and underwent a change in head teacher fairly soon after. The result of the changes made by school leadership led to an improvement in grades in the next years GCSE\u2019s. Following the success in 2012 and 2013, the school came out of special measures and has been progressing well. <ref> Ofsted Reports on Tavistock College Multi-Academy Trust https://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/23/145336 </ref>\n\nIn 2013, a Japanese teacher won the so-called \"teachers' Oscar\" for secondary teacher of the year.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-24551445 Devon teacher wins 'Oscar' for Japanese lessons] BBC News, 20 October 2013</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=May 2019}}\nTavistock grammar school was founded in 1552. In the 1930s it stood \"on the Plymouth road, a modern block with splendid playing fields\" but was later moved to the current site to allow for expansion as Tavistock and surrounding areas grew in population. <ref>Mee, A.. ed. ''The King's England: Devon'' London: Hodder and Stoughton, 1938, p. 415</ref>\n\nThe college motto was traditionally \u201cCrescit sub pondere virtus\u201d (Virtue flourishes under a burden); this is also the motto of the [[Earl of Denbigh]]. However, the school motto was changed to \u201cTogether: we care, we challenge, we excel\u201d\n\n==Other activities==\nSince 2006, the college has organised concerts locally under the name of ParkLife; a ParkLife festival was held in 2007 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parklifeparty.co.uk/index2.php|title=Parklife Party Homepage|work=Parklife website|accessdate=28 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nTavistock College regularly takes students to remote regions of the world on expeditions with companies such as Camps International <ref> Camps International - Ethical Journeys with Impact https://www.campsinternational.com/ </ref>\n\nThe college has also participated in fundraising activities and community tasks such as dog shows, the school sports day, local athletics competitions hosted on the extensive track and PE facilities.\n===Sports===\nOver \u00a31.1m has been invested in new sporting facilities - an all-weather pitch, competition standard athletics track, and a football pitch development comprising seven pitches over the past years. The college Rugby and Football teams all extensively utilise these facilities as well as allowing local clubs such as Tavistock FC to train on the Astro on a regular basis. The track and other athletics facilities are regularly used for athletics clubs and for hosting competitions.\n\nMost years the college engages in school \u201cSports Tours\u201d with the Rugby, Football and netball teams to foreign destinations such as France, Italy or America where the teams compete over multiple tournaments during the trip.\n==Notable former pupils==\n* [[Trevor Colman]] politician, a Member of the European Parliament for South West England\n* [[Graham Dawe]], rugby union player\n* [[Robert Hingley]], pioneering [[ska]] musician\n* [[Rosie Huntington-Whiteley]], actress/model, came from a nearby farm; she is known for ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/100524-rosie-huntingtonwhiteley-biography.aspx|title=Rosie Huntington-Whiteley|last=Milligan|first=Lauren|date=17 May 2010|publisher=[[Vogue UK]]|accessdate=30 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201235454/http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/100524-rosie-huntingtonwhiteley-biography.aspx|archivedate=1 December 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Sam Lakeman]], [[Seth Lakeman]] and [[Sean Lakeman]], folk musicians\n* [[Greg Parker (physicist)|Greg Parker]], Professor of Photonics at Southampton University\n*[[Ben Rich (weather forecaster)|Ben Rich]], BBC weather presenter\n* [[Ryan Waker]](BOAS CertIbo)| Nuclear/Mechanical Engineering Specialist\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tavistockcollege.org/ Official website]\n* [http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_providers/full/%28urn%29/113539 Ofsted report on Tavistock College]\n* [http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/councildemocracy/deliveringservices/directorates_and_departments/chief_executive_s/communication/news_service/press-releases/press-release.htm?id=2732 \"Tavistock College aims for swift improvements and rising standards\" Press Release from Devon County Council, 26 March 2010]\n{{Schools in Devon}}\n\n{{Coord|50.54157|N|4.15461|W|type:edu_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Devon]]\n[[Category:Foundation schools in Devon]]\n[[Category:Tavistock]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Tavistock College\n | image                   = Cresttavcoll.jpg\n | image_size              = 150\n | motto                   = Together: we care, we challenge, we excel\n | established             = 1552\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Foundation school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | president               = \n | head_label              = Principal\n | head                    = Sarah Jones<ref>[http://tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/ Tavistock College web site.] Retrieved September 18, 2015.</ref>\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = Chair\n | chair                   = Mandy Govier\n | founder                 = \n | address                 = Crowndale Rd\n | city                    = [[Tavistock, Devon|Tavistock]]\n | county                  = [[Devon]]\n | country                 = [[England]]\n | postcode                = PL19 8DD\n | local_authority         = [[Devon County Council|Devon]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | dfeno                   = \n | urn                     = 113539\n | staff                   = 300\n | enrolment               = approx. 1800\n | gender                  = [[Coeducational]]\n | lower_age               = 11\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = {{color box|#FF0000}} Bedford \n{{color box|#008000}} Drake\n\n{{color box|#800080}} Fitzford\n\n{{color box|#FFFF00}} Glanville\n\n{{color box|#0000FF}} Tremayne\n | colours                 = \n | publication             = In Focus\n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://www.tavistockcollege.org\n}}\n\n'''Tavistock College''' is a mixed gender [[state school|state-funded]] in [[Tavistock, Devon|Tavistock]], [[Devon]], England, with students aged 11\u201318. There were (as of April 2020) approximately 1700 students attending.The schools draws students from a catchment area of about {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} radius.\n\nThe college has links with Japan, [[Uganda]], Spain, Swaziland, Peru, France and India where staff exchanges and student visits and projects take place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/college/|title=The College|publisher=Tavistock College|work=Tavistock College website|accessdate=2007-06-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610041642/http://www.tavistockcollege.devon.sch.uk/college/|archivedate=2007-06-10}}</ref>\n==Ofsted Reviews==\nIn early 2010, the school received a \"notice to improve\" from [[Ofsted]], the national school inspection agency.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.tavistock-today.co.uk/article.cfm?id=461&headline=Ofsted%20tells%20college%20it%20must%20improve&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2009 | title=Ofsted tells college it must improve |date= 12 February 2009| newspaper =Tavistock Today|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> After a failure to improve, the following year Tavistock College was placed under special measures. \nThe school was placed into special measures in September 2011 and underwent a change in head teacher fairly soon after. The result of the changes made by school leadership led to an improvement in grades in the next years GCSE\u2019s. Following the success in 2012 and 2013, the school came out of special measures and has been progressing well. <ref> Ofsted Reports on Tavistock College Multi-Academy Trust https://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/23/145336 </ref>\n\nIn 2013, a Japanese teacher won the so-called \"teachers' Oscar\" for secondary teacher of the year.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-24551445 Devon teacher wins 'Oscar' for Japanese lessons] BBC News, 20 October 2013</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=May 2019}}\nTavistock grammar school was founded in 1552. In the 1930s it stood \"on the Plymouth road, a modern block with splendid playing fields\" but was later moved to the current site to allow for expansion as Tavistock and surrounding areas grew in population. <ref>Mee, A.. ed. ''The King's England: Devon'' London: Hodder and Stoughton, 1938, p. 415</ref>\n\nThe college motto was traditionally \u201cCrescit sub pondere virtus\u201d (Virtue flourishes under a burden); this is also the motto of the [[Earl of Denbigh]]. However, the school motto was changed to \u201cTogether: we care, we challenge, we excel\u201d\n\n==Other activities==\nSince 2006, the college has organised concerts locally under the name of ParkLife; a ParkLife festival was held in 2007 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parklifeparty.co.uk/index2.php|title=Parklife Party Homepage|work=Parklife website|accessdate=28 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nTavistock College regularly takes students to remote regions of the world on expeditions with companies such as Camps International <ref> Camps International - Ethical Journeys with Impact https://www.campsinternational.com/ </ref>\n\nThe college has also participated in fundraising activities and community tasks such as dog shows, the school sports day, local athletics competitions hosted on the extensive track and PE facilities.\n===Sports===\nOver \u00a31.1m has been invested in new sporting facilities - an all-weather pitch, competition standard athletics track, and a football pitch development comprising seven pitches over the past years. The college Rugby and Football teams all extensively utilise these facilities as well as allowing local clubs such as Tavistock FC to train on the Astro on a regular basis. The track and other athletics facilities are regularly used for athletics clubs and for hosting competitions.\n\nMost years the college engages in school \u201cSports Tours\u201d with the Rugby, Football and netball teams to foreign destinations such as France, Italy or America where the teams compete over multiple tournaments during the trip.\n==Notable former pupils==\n* [[Trevor Colman]] politician, a Member of the European Parliament for South West England\n* [[Graham Dawe]], rugby union player\n* [[Robert Hingley]], pioneering [[ska]] musician\n* [[Rosie Huntington-Whiteley]], actress/model, came from a nearby farm; she is known for ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/100524-rosie-huntingtonwhiteley-biography.aspx|title=Rosie Huntington-Whiteley|last=Milligan|first=Lauren|date=17 May 2010|publisher=[[Vogue UK]]|accessdate=30 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201235454/http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/100524-rosie-huntingtonwhiteley-biography.aspx|archivedate=1 December 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Sam Lakeman]], [[Seth Lakeman]] and [[Sean Lakeman]], folk musicians\n* [[Greg Parker (physicist)|Greg Parker]], Professor of Photonics at Southampton University\n*[[Ben Rich (weather forecaster)|Ben Rich]], BBC weather presenter\n* [[Ryan Waker]](BOAS CertIbo)| Nuclear/Mechanical Engineering Specialist\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tavistockcollege.org/ Official website]\n* [http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_providers/full/%28urn%29/113539 Ofsted report on Tavistock College]\n* [http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/councildemocracy/deliveringservices/directorates_and_departments/chief_executive_s/communication/news_service/press-releases/press-release.htm?id=2732 \"Tavistock College aims for swift improvements and rising standards\" Press Release from Devon County Council, 26 March 2010]\n{{Schools in Devon}}\n\n{{Coord|50.54157|N|4.15461|W|type:edu_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Devon]]\n[[Category:Foundation schools in Devon]]\n[[Category:Tavistock]]\n", "name_user": "MaxWBooth", "label": "safe", "comment": "A small correction to align with most up to date figures.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tavistock_College"}
{"title_page": "Yvonne De Carlo", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian-American actress, dancer, and singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Yvonne De Carlo\n| image      = YvonneDC.jpg\n| caption    = De Carlo c. 1950s\n| birth_name  = Margaret Yvonne Middleton\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1922|9|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2007|1|8|1922|9|1|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actress, dancer, singer\n| years_active = 1939\u20131995\n| notable_works = [[Zipporah|Sephora]] from [[Cecil B. DeMille]]'s ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)\n| television = ''[[The Munsters]]'' (1964\u20131966)\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Robert Drew Morgan|1955|1973|end=div}}\n| children = 2\n| module     = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| instrument = Vocals\n| genre = {{Flat list|\n* [[Blues]]\n* [[jazz]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| label = {{Flat list|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Imperial Records|Imperial]]\n* Masterseal ([[Remington Records|Remington]])\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Yvonne De Carlo''' (born '''Margaret Yvonne Middleton'''; September 1, 1922 \u2013 January 8, 2007) was a [[Canadian]]-American actress, dancer, and singer. A brunette with blue-grey eyes, she became an internationally famous [[Hollywood]] film star in the [[1940s in film|1940s]] and [[1950s in film|1950s]], made several recordings, and later acted on television and stage.\n\nBorn in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], De Carlo was raised in the home of her Presbyterian maternal grandparents. Her mother enrolled her in a local dance school when she was three. By the early 1940s, she and her mother had moved to Los Angeles, where De Carlo participated in beauty contests and worked as a dancer in nightclubs.\n\nShe began working in motion pictures in 1941, in short subjects. She sang \"The Lamp of Memory\" in a three-minute [[Soundies]] musical, and worked briefly at [[Columbia Pictures]]. In 1942, she signed a three-year contract with [[Paramount Pictures]], where she was given uncredited bit parts in important films and was intended to replace [[Dorothy Lamour]]. Her first lead was for independent producer [[E. B. Derr]] in the [[James Fenimore Cooper]] adventure ''[[The Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]'' (1943, ultimately released by [[Republic Pictures]]).\n\nShe obtained her breakthrough role in ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945), a [[Universal Pictures]] release produced by [[Walter Wanger]], who described her as \"the most beautiful girl in the world.\"<ref name=\"Most Beautiful Girl Discovered'\">{{cite news|title=\"Most Beautiful Girl\" Discovered|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1338&dat=19440918&id=a91YAAAAIBAJ&pg=5975,3223468|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]]|date=September 18, 1944}}</ref><ref name=\"Salome, Where She Danced Comes to Harris'\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Harold V.|title=\"Salome, Where She Danced\" Comes to Harris|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19450507&id=bbhRAAAAIBAJ&pg=3004,542086|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=May 7, 1945}}</ref><ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'\">{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19450725&id=Mb4tAAAAIBAJ&pg=4893,3527502|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|date=July 25, 1945}}</ref> The film's publicity and success turned her into a star, and she signed a five-year contract with Universal. From then on, Universal starred her in its lavish Technicolor productions, such as ''[[Frontier Gal]]'' (1945), ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947), and ''[[Slave Girl (film)|Slave Girl]]'' (1947). Cameramen voted her \"Queen of Technicolor\" three years in a row.<ref name=\"Slave Girl Wants Freedom\">{{cite news|last=Willett|first=Bob|title=Slave Girl Wants Freedom: Tired of playing exotic sirens, Canada's lovely Yvonne De Carlo seeks more serious film roles|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19541113&id=YPkwAAAAIBAJ&pg=5353,3064717|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=November 13, 1954}}</ref> Tired of being typecast as exotic women, she made her first serious dramatic performances in two [[film noir|films noir]], ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947) and ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949).\n\nThe first American film star to visit [[Israel]], De Carlo received further recognition as an actress for her work in the British comedies ''[[Hotel Sahara]]'' (1951) and ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953). Her career reached its peak when eminent producer-director [[Cecil B. DeMille]] cast her as [[Moses]]' [[Midian]]ite wife, [[Zipporah|Sephora]], her most prominent role, in his biblical epic ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956),<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2008\">{{cite book|last=Jacob Sparks|first=Karen|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=2008|isbn=9781593394257|page=123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wKvMZWcgKYC&dq=cecil+b+demille+yvonne+de+carlo&q=Yvonne+De+Carlo}}</ref> which was immensely successful at the box office and remains an annual tradition on television. Her success continued with starring roles in ''[[Flame of the Islands]]'' (1956), ''[[Death of a Scoundrel]]'' (1956), ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957), and ''[[The Sword and the Cross]]'' (1958), in which she portrayed [[Mary Magdalene]]. She also accepted supporting roles in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963) and ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964).\n\nShe gained a new generation of fans as a star of the CBS sitcom ''[[The Munsters]]'' (1964\u20131966),<ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Is The Mama In a Nice Monster Family\">{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo Is The Mama In a Nice Monster Family|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19640623&id=nWJSAAAAIBAJ&pg=5511,1718564|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=June 23, 1964}}</ref> playing [[Herman Munster]]'s glamorous [[vampire]] wife, [[Lily Munster|Lily]], a role she reprised in the feature film ''[[Munster, Go Home!]]'' (1966) and the television film ''[[The Munsters' Revenge]]'' (1981). In 1971, she played Carlotta Campion and introduced the popular song \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\" in the Broadway production of the [[Stephen Sondheim]] musical ''[[Follies]]''. ''Yvonne'', her best-selling autobiography, was published in 1987. A stroke survivor, De Carlo died of heart failure in 2007. She was awarded two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] for her contributions to motion pictures and television.\n\n==Early life==\n{{quote box\n |class = <!-- Advanced users only.  See the \"Custom classes\" section below. -->\n |title = \n |quote = On the evening of August 31 that year [1922], three days after her own birthday, Marie was having five-minute contractions. She was taken to the public ward of St. Paul's Hospital, where she went through a difficult labor. I was born the following morning amid the tumult of the season's worst thunderstorm. Marie's doctor hadn't arrived, and the delivery was made by a pair of floor nurses. They confirmed afterward that as she was being shifted to the delivery table, she was shouting, \"I want a girl. It must be a girl. I want a dancer!\"\n |author = \u2014Yvonne De Carlo\n |source = ''Yvonne: An Autobiography''{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}}\n |width  = 300px\n}}\n\nDe Carlo was born Margaret Yvonne Middleton on September 1, 1922, at [[St. Paul's Hospital (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Hospital]]{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada. Her nickname was \"Peggy\" because she was named after the silent film star [[Diana Serra Cary|Baby Peggy]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Her mother, Marie De Carlo (August 28, 1903 \u2013 December 19, 1993),<ref name='Marie Decarlo Middleton, \"California, Death Index, 1940-1997\"'>{{cite web|title=Marie Decarlo Middleton, \"California, Death Index, 1940-1997\"|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/VGPY-72X|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> was born in [[France]] to a [[Sicily|Sicilian]] father and a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother. Marie, a \"wayward and rebellious\" teenager, had aspired to become a dancer and worked as a milliner's apprentice until she met Peggy's father, William Shelto Middleton,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} a salesman from [[New Zealand]]<ref name=\"The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo\">{{cite news|last1=Bang|first1=Maureen|title=The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/45653015?searchTerm=yvonne%20de%20carlo%20new%20zealand&searchLimits=|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=The Australian Women's Weekly|date=November 15, 1972}}</ref> with \"piercing eyes of pale blue, and a wealth of straight black hair.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} Marie and William married in [[Alberta]], where they lived for a couple of months before returning to Vancouver.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} They moved in with Marie's parents, but the marriage was troubled.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=15}} Peggy had only two memories of her father: climbing up to his knee and crawling towards his feet.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=15}} By the time Peggy was three,{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=82}} William was involved in various swindles and fled Canada aboard a [[schooner]], promising to send for his wife and child.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} Marie and Peggy never heard from him again; rumors said that he remarried twice and had more children, worked as an actor in silent films, or died aboard a ship.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Peggy later wrote, \"My own assumption is that he died before he had the chance to discover that his Baby Peggy had become a Hollywood actress, or I think he would have tried to contact me.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}}\n\nAfter William's departure, Marie left her parents' home and found work in a shop.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Marie and Peggy lived in a succession of apartments in Vancouver, including one that had no furniture or stove,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} and periodically returned to the De Carlo home, \"a huge white frame house\", at 1728 Comox Street in Vancouver's [[West End, Vancouver|West End]] neighborhood.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}} Marie's parents, Michele \"Papa\" De Carlo ({{circa}} 1873 \u2013 July 1, 1954)<ref name='Michael Decarlo, \"British Columbia Death Registrations, 1872-1986\"'>{{cite web|title=Michael Decarlo, \"British Columbia Death Registrations, 1872-1986\"|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-266-11671-106563-72?cc=1538285|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> and Margaret Purvis De Carlo (December 30, 1874 \u2013 October 26, 1949),<ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Decarlo - British Columbia Death Registrations|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FLRW-VLP|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> were religious, attended church regularly, and held services in the parlor.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=20}} Michele, a native of the city of [[Messina]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Michele De Carlo mentioned in the record of Kenneth Ross McKenzie and Constance Marguerite Anna Decarlo|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HY-DRGQ-DRB|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> had met Margaret in [[Nice]], France. They married in 1897, had four children, and settled in Canada.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=19}}\n\nDe Carlo attended Lord Roberts Elementary School,<ref name=\"History of Vancouver website\">{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/archives_yvonne.htm|website=History of Vancouver|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> located a block away from her grandparents' home.\n\nDe Carlo originally wanted to be a writer.<ref name=\"'Some day I'll meet Mr. Right'\">{{cite news|last1=Nash|first1=Roy|title=Some day I'll meet Mr. Right|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131240078|accessdate=18 March 2018|work=The News|date=November 28, 1953}}</ref> She was seven when a school assignment, a poem she wrote titled \"A Little Boy\", was entered in a contest run by ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}} She won and received a prize of five dollars, which according to De Carlo, meant as much to her at that time as if she had won the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=127}} She also wrote short plays, which she usually staged in her grandparents' house, and even adapted [[Charles Dickens]]' ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' for a neighborhood performance.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=127}}\n\nMarie wanted her daughter to have a career in show business and made sure Peggy received the necessary singing and dancing lessons. Peggy joined the choir of [[St. Paul's Anglican Church (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Anglican Church]] to strengthen her voice,<ref name=\"Films in Review, Volume 28\">{{cite book|title=Films in Review, Volume 28|date=1977|publisher=National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|page=217}}</ref> and when she was ten (or three, according to a 1982 interview{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}}), her mother enrolled her in the June Roper School of the Dance in Vancouver.<ref name=\"pryor\">\"The Unveiling of Yvonne (Salome) De Carlo: Herewith Some Early Film Entries in the Easter Week Sweepstakes\" by Thomas M. Pryor. ''New York Times'', March 25, 1945, p. X3.</ref> In May 1939, a ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' news item listed \"Yvonne de Carlo\" as one of the performers at the opening of Hy Singer's Palomar ballroom (also known as Palomar Supper Club) in Vancouver.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vancouver Dancery Opens As Night Club|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety134-1939-05#page/n39/mode/2up/search/yvonne+de+carlo|accessdate=18 March 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 3, 1939|page=41}}</ref>\n\n==Early Career==\n===Beginnings in Hollywood (1940\u20131942)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Maxie Rosenbloom in Harvard, Here I Come.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo in her first feature film, ''[[Harvard, Here I Come!]]'' (1941), starring boxer [[Maxie Rosenbloom]] (center)]]\nDe Carlo and her mother made several trips to [[Los Angeles]]. In 1940, she won second place in the Miss [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice]] beauty contest,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=4}} and placed fifth in that year's [[Miss California]] competition (and can be seen in that pageant at 0:36 of the British Path\u00e9 film \"A Matter of Figures\").<ref>\"Schoolgirl, 17 and Blond, Chosen as Miss California: Crowd of 100,000 Sees Parade of 50 Beauties as Venice Brings Four-Day Mardi Gras to Close\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' 12 August 1940: A1.</ref> At the Miss Venice contest, she was noticed by a booking agent who told her to audition for an opening in the chorus line at the [[Earl Carroll Theatre]] on Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=4}} De Carlo and her mother arrived at Earl Carroll's for the audition, but after learning that Carroll would have to examine her \"upper assets\" before hiring her,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=5}} De Carlo and her mother searched for work at another popular Hollywood nightclub, the Florentine Gardens.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=6}} They met N. T. G. -- [[Nils Granlund]], the proprietor of the Florentine Gardens\u2014who introduced De Carlo to the audience before she tap danced to \"[[Tea for Two (song)|Tea for Two]]\".{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=7}} Granlund then asked, \"Well, folks ... is she in or out?\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=8}} The audience responded with \"a rousing round of applause, with whistles and cheers,\" and De Carlo got the job.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoefling|first1=Larry J.|title=Nils Thor Granlund: Show Business Entrepreneur and America's First Radio Star|date=2008|publisher=Inlandia Press|location=Oklahoma|isbn=978-0-7864-4849-4|pages=178\u2013181|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VTfrVOw8c_0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> She started in the back of the chorus line, but after months of practice and hard work,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=10}} Granlund featured her in a \"[[King Kong]] number.\" In it, she danced, and cast off several chiffon veils before being carried away by a gorilla.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=11}} She was given more solo routines and also appeared in her first soundie.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=11}} She had been dancing at the Florentine Gardens only a few months when she was arrested by immigration officials and deported to Canada in late 1940.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=12}} In January 1941, Granlund sent a telegram to immigration officials pledging his sponsorship of De Carlo in the U.S., and affirmed his offer of steady employment, both requirements to reenter the country.<ref>Hoefling, p. 182.</ref>\n\nIn May 1941, she appeared in a revue, ''Hollywood Revels'', at the [[Orpheum Theatre (Los Angeles)|Orpheum Theatre]]. A critic from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reviewed it saying that the \"dancing of Yvonne de Carlo is especially notable.\"<ref>Kingsley, Grace. \"Bright Bill at Orpheum\", ''Los Angeles Times'', May 22, 1941, pg. 12.</ref> She made her radio debut with [[Edmund Lowe]] and [[Victor McLaglen]] who were performing extracts from a series based on their Flagg-Quint performances.<ref>De Carlo p 58</ref>\n\nDe Carlo wanted to act. At the encouragement of [[Artie Shaw]] who offered to pay her wage for a month,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=59}} she quit the Florentine Gardens and hired a talent agent, Jack Pomeroy.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=60}} Pomeroy got De Carlo an uncredited role as a bathing beauty in a [[Columbia Pictures]] [[B film]], ''[[Harvard, Here I Come]]'' (1941). She had one line (\"Nowadays a girl must show a front\") in a scene with the film's star, [[Maxie Rosenbloom]]. Her salary was $25 and her work in the film got her into the [[Screen Actors Guild]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=60}} While at Columbia, she was featured (in a swimsuit) in ''The Kink of the Campus'', a short slapstick comedy with music, produced by the [[Three Stooges]] production team. Other roles were slow to follow, and De Carlo took a job in the chorus line of [[Earl Carroll]].\n\nWhile working for Carroll De Carlo got a one-line part in ''[[This Gun for Hire]]'' (1942) at Paramount. Carroll found out and fired her. De Carlo returned to N. T. G. at the Florentine Gardens.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=62}}\n\nIn December 1941, she was dancing in the revue ''Glamour Over Hollywood'' at Florentine Gardens.<ref>\"Travel: Taxco Basks in Grandeur and Beauty of Early Days\" ''Los Angeles Times'', December 28, 1941, pg. C4.</ref>{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=63}} America's entry into World War Two saw De Carlo and other Florentine dancers busy entertaining troops at USO shows.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=67}}<ref>\"Yvonne DeCarlo: Gilded Lily\". ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' (July 18, 2000).</ref>\n\nA skilled horsewoman, she appeared in a number of West Coast rodeos.<ref name=\"pryor\"/>\n\n===Paramount Pictures (1942\u20131944)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Deerslayer.jpg|thumb|De Carlo as Wah-Tah in ''[[Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]'' (1943)]]\nDe Carlo was cast as an island girl in ''[[Road to Morocco]]'' (1942) at Paramount. She was given a screen test for a role in ''[[The Moon and Sixpence (film)|The Moon and Sixpence]]'', but lost the part to Elena Verdugo. Paramount called her back for a small part in ''[[Lucky Jordan]]'' (also 1942) and she was cast in film for [[Republic Pictures|Republic]], ''[[Youth on Parade]]'' (again 1942), which she called a \"dreadful ... bomb\".<ref>De Carlo p. 70</ref>\n\nParamount then offered De Carlo a six-month contract, possibly going up to seven years, starting at $60 a week. She served as an extra in Paramount's ''[[The Crystal Ball (film)|The Crystal Ball]]'' (1943) of which she wrote \"only my left shoulder survived after editing\".<ref>De Carlo p 71</ref> Her scenes in ''[[Lucky Jordan]]'' (1942) were deleted but she had a small role in ''[[For Whom the Bell Tolls (film)|For Whom the Bell Tolls]]'' (1943). She could also be seen in ''[[Let's Face It (film)|Let's Face It]]'' (1943), ''[[So Proudly We Hail!]]'' (1943) and ''[[Salute for Three]]'' (1943), She was also kept busy in small roles and helping other actors shoot tests. \"I was the test queen at Paramount,\" she said later.<ref name=\"pryor\"/> But De Carlo was ambitious and wanted more. \"I'm not going to be just one of the girls,\" she said.<ref name=\"new\"/>\n\n[[Cecil B. DeMille]] saw De Carlo in ''So Proudly We Hail!'', and arranged for a screen-test and interview for the role of Tremartini in his film ''[[The Story of Dr. Wassell]]'' (1943), and subsequently chose her for a key role.<ref>\"Drama: 'Cousin' Rewrite Set; Hubbard Joining Cast\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', February 18, 1943, pg. A8.</ref><ref>\"Drama and Film: Gladys George Named Bankhead Successor Edward Small Plans Picture Glorifying Famous Maternity Center in Chicago\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', July 3, 1943, pg. 8.</ref> He ended up choosing [[Carol Thurston]] for the role and casting De Carlo in an uncredited part as a native girl, but promised to \"make it up\" to De Carlo on another film \"in the future.\"{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=110}}\n\nShe took two freelance assignments in 1943. When N. T. G. was signed by [[Monogram Pictures]] to film his revue for ''[[Rhythm Parade]]'', he recruited DeCarlo, who appears in the film as a Florentine Gardens dancer. She then took a leading role in ''[[The Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]''.\n\nShe returned to Paramount for an unbilled bit in ''[[True to Life (film)|True to Life]]'' (1943) and ''[[Standing Room Only (1944 film)|Standing Room Only]]'' (1944). De Carlo was billed in a short, ''Fun Time'' (1944) and went to [[MGM]] to play another \"native\" part (unbilled) in ''[[Kismet (1944 film)|Kismet]]'' (1944).\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' later dubbed De Carlo \"threat girl\" for [[Dorothy Lamour]] \"when Dotty wanted to break away from saronging.\"{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=110}}<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo, Technicolor Queen\">{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Sheilah|title=Yvonne DeCarlo, Technicolor Queen|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19490924&id=JC0sAAAAIBAJ&pg=4692,7182143|accessdate=April 28, 2014|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=September 24, 1949}}</ref> This had its origin when De Carlo was set to replace Dorothy Lamour in the lead of ''[[Rainbow Island (1944 film)|Rainbow Island]]'' (1944); however Lamour changed her mind about playing the role.<ref name=\"new\">\"Yvonne De Carlo Stands Out Again as 'Threat Girl': Carroll Cutie Has Spotlight in Sarong Set Yvonne De Carlo Causes Concern in Sarong Circles\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', June 3, 1945, pg. B1.</ref> De Carlo was given a bit part in the final movie.\n\nDe Carlo played further unbilled roles in ''[[Here Come the Waves]]'' (1944), ''[[Practically Yours]]'' (1944), and ''[[Bring On the Girls (film)|Bring on the Girls]]'' (1945). Paramount then decided not to renew her contract option<ref>De Carlo p 84</ref> but renewed Lamour's contract.\n\n==Stardom==\n===''Salome, Where She Danced'' (1944\u20131945)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Salome, Where She Danced.jpg|thumbnail|De Carlo as Anna Maria, an Austrian dancer, in ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945)]]\nDe Carlo was screen tested by [[Universal Pictures|Universal]], who were looking for an exotic glamour girl in the mold of [[Maria Montez]] and [[Acquanetta]].<ref>De Carlo p. 84</ref> The test was seen by [[Walter Wanger]] who was making an adventure film in Technicolor, ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945). Wanger later claimed he discovered De Carlo when looking at footage for another actor in which De Carlo also happened to appear ([[Milburn Stone]]).<ref>\"Hollywood Memoranda: Noted in Hollywood\", ''New York Times'', September 24, 1944, pg. X1.</ref>\n\nWanger tested De Carlo several times and Universal signed her to a long term contract at $150 a week. In September 1944, it was announced De Carlo was cast in the lead of ''Salome'' over a reported 20,000 other young women.<ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'\"/><ref>Schallert, Edwin. \"Guild Player Deemed Fit Valentino Double: David Bruce Wins Acting Opportunity in Wanger's Film Drama, ''Salome''\" ''Los Angeles Times'', September 19, 1944, pg. A8.</ref>\n\nAnother source says 21 Royal Canadian Air Force bombardier students who loved her as a pinup star campaigned to get her the role.<ref>\"From Pinup to Star!\", ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', November 12, 1944, p. D5.</ref> De Carlo later said this was done at her behest; she took several pictures of herself in a revealing costume and persuaded two childhood friends from Vancouver, Reginald Reid and Kenneth Ross McKenzie, who had become pilots, to arrange their friends to lobby on her behalf,<ref name=\"pryor\"/> writing in her memoirs that the whole thing was Wanger's idea.<ref>De Carlo p. 89</ref>\n\nThough not a critical success, ''Salome'' was a box office favorite, and the heavily promoted De Carlo was hailed as an up-and-coming star. In his review for the film, [[Bosley Crowther]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote:\n\n<blockquote>Miss De Carlo has an agreeable contralto singing voice, all the 'looks' one girl could ask for, and, moreover, she dances with a sensuousness which must have caused the [[Motion Picture Production Code|Hays office]] some anguish. The script, however, does not give her much chance to prove her acting talents.<ref name=\"Salome Where She Danced (1945) The Screen; 'Rose's Diamond Horseshoe,' With Betty Grable, at Roxy-- 'Salome, Where She Danced,' Is Newcomer of the Criterion At Loew's\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Salome Where She Danced (1945) The Screen; 'Rose's Diamond Horseshoe,' With Betty Grable, at Roxy-- 'Salome, Where She Danced,' Is Newcomer of the Criterion At Loew's|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9c07e3df143bee3bbc4b53dfb366838e659ede|accessdate=April 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 3, 1945}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Universal-International (1945\u20131950)===\n[[File:Yvonne in Song of Scheherezade.jpg|thumb|De Carlo in the trailer for ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947)]]\n''Salome, Where She Danced'' was released by Universal who signed de Carlo to a long-term contract. She was used by the studio as a backup star to [[Maria Montez]], and her second movie for the studio saw her step into a role rejected by Montez: the Western ''[[Frontier Gal]]'' (1946) alongside Rod Cameron.<ref name=\"new\"/> In 1946, exhibitors voted De Carlo the ninth-most promising \"star of tomorrow.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17994035|title=The Stars of To-morrow|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=September 10, 1946|accessdate=April 24, 2012|page=11|publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Like ''Salome'', it was shot in Technicolor.\n\nDe Carlo followed ''Frontier Gal'' with a top-billed role in [[Walter Reisch]]'s Technicolor musical ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947), co-starring [[Brian Donlevy]] and [[Jean-Pierre Aumont]]. [[Tilly Losch]], an Austrian dancer and friend of Reisch, coached De Carlo in her three dancing solos.<ref>De Carlo p. 114</ref> The film was a hit, making over $2 million.\n\nDe Carlo wanted to act in different types of movies. She applied to play the part of a waitress in ''[[A Double Life (1947 film)|A Double Life]]'' (1947) but lost out to [[Shelley Winters]].<ref>De Carlo p 122</ref> Instead, Universal put her back in Technicolor for ''[[Slave Girl (film)|Slave Girl]]'' (1947), made with the producers of ''Frontier Gal''. It was another solid commercial success. De Carlo was given a small role in ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947), a prison movie starring [[Burt Lancaster]] and produced by [[Mark Hellinger]]. It was her first movie in black and white since becoming a star and her first to get good reviews.\n\nShe played [[Lola Montez]] in ''[[Black Bart (film)|Black Bart]]'' (1948), a Technicolor Western with [[Dan Duryea]] for director [[George Sherman]]. Duryea and Sherman worked with her again on ''[[River Lady (film)|River Lady]]'' (1948). De Carlo called these films \"physically taxing but not creatively inspiring.\"<ref>De Carlo p 127</ref> The ''New York Times'' later summarised them as \"a series of routine costume adventures as a tough but good-natured minx from across the tracks who wades into society and inevitably backtracks with a bloke of her own caliber.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/06/21/archives/yvonne-de-carlo-in-technicolor-feature.html|newspaper=New York Times|title=Yvonne de Carlo in Technicolor Feature|last=H. H. T.|date=June 21, 1952}}</ref>\n\nShe romanced Tony Martin in ''[[Casbah (film)|Casbah]]'' (1948), a musical remake of ''[[Algiers (film)|Algiers]]'' (1938) made for Martin's own production company but released through Universal. De Carlo was reluctant to be in it because, though she would receive top billing over Martin, she did not get the female lead. That part went to Swedish newcomer [[M\u00e4rta Tor\u00e9n]]. However, studio head [[William Goetz]] insisted<ref>De Carlo p 129</ref> that De Carlo play Inez, the role [[Sigrid Gurie]] acted in the 1938 version. She also sang the film's song ''For Every Man There's a Woman'', which was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. The film flopped at the box office, de Carlo's first flop since becoming a star.\n\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Criss Cross.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo in the trailer for ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949)]]\nDe Carlo then received an offer from Mark Hellinger to make another film with Burt Lancaster: the [[film noir]] ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949). This time De Carlo had a larger role, as a femme fatale, Anna. [[Bosley Crowther]] noted that De Carlo was \"trying something different as Anna. The change is welcome, even though Miss de Carlo's performance is uneven. In that respect, she is right in step with most everything else about ''Criss Cross.''\"<ref name=\"Criss Cross (1948) Burt Lancaster Same Old Tough Guy\">{{cite news|title=Movie Review: Criss Cross (1948) Burt Lancaster Same Old Tough Guy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9403E5D7103EE03BBC4A52DFB5668382659EDE|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 12, 1949}}</ref> The film has become regarded as a classic and De Carlo considered the role the highlight of her career to date.<ref>Strong, E J., \"Yvonne De Carlo May Brave Suspension, So She Can Return to Troops: GI's Show Needs Told by Actress\", ''Los Angeles Times'', October 3, 1948, pg. D1.</ref> [[Tony Curtis]] made his debut in the movie, in a scene dancing with De Carlo.\n\nDe Carlo was keen to make more movies along this line but Universal put her back in Technicolor Westerns with ''[[Calamity Jane and Sam Bass]]'' (1949), playing [[Calamity Jane]], directed by Sherman, alongside [[Howard Duff]].\n\nShe played a role intended for [[Deanna Durbin]] in ''[[The Gal Who Took the West]]'' (1950), for director [[Fred de Cordova]]. The movie gave her a chance to show off her singing voice. Trained in opera and a former child chorister at St Paul's Anglican Church, Vancouver, De Carlo possessed a large [[vocal range]].<ref name='\"The Independent\" obituary'>{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo [Obituary]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/yvonne-de-carlo-431761.html|accessdate=January 11, 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|quote=Impressed with her large vocal range ...}}</ref> She was meant to be in ''[[Bagdad (film)|Bagdad]]'' (1949) but suffered a miscarriage and was ill, so the studio cast [[Maureen O'Hara]].<ref>de Carlo p 145</ref>\n\nDe Cordova directed de Carlo in ''[[Buccaneer's Girl]]'' (1950), a pirate movie set in 1810s New Orleans opposite [[Philip Friend]]. The director later called De Carlo \"a doll ... underrated as an actress. She was most professional, worked hard, was very good at her craft, possibly was not a first class star but came in on schedule. She knew her lines, she danced and sang rather well, and she wanted very much to be a bigger star than she ever became.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/justmakingmovies00davi#page/132/mode/1up|title=Just Making Movies: Company Directors on the Studio System|page=132|first=Roland L.|last=Davis|publisher=University of Press Mississippi|year=2005}}</ref>\n\nShe toured US army bases singing, then was in ''[[The Desert Hawk (1950 film)|The Desert Hawk]]'' (1950), an \"Eastern\" with [[Richard Greene]]. She made a Western with Sherman, ''[[Tomahawk (film)|Tomahawk]]'' (1951), opposite [[Van Heflin]], which was popular.\n\nDe Carlo toured extensively to promote her films and entertained US troops in Europe. She also began singing on television.<ref>Yvonne De Carlo Pins Hopes for Future on Switch to Dramatic and Singing Roles SCHUER, PHILIP K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]27 May 1951: D1.</ref>\n\nShe received an offer from England to make a comedy, ''[[Hotel Sahara]]'' (1951) with [[Peter Ustinov]]. While in England, she asked Universal to release her from her contract, though it still had three months to go, and the studio agreed.<ref>Brady, Thomas F. \"Paramount Buys Two New Stories: Giler Melodrama and Clark Adventure Acquired by Studio --Jean Arthur Gets Role\", ''New York Times'', January 30, 1951, pg. 21.</ref>\n\n===Post-Universal (1951\u20131954)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and John Ireland in Hurricane Smith.jpg|thumb|De Carlo and fellow Vancouverite [[John Ireland (actor)|John Ireland]] in ''[[Hurricane Smith (1952 film)|Hurricane Smith]]'' (1952), a Paramount Pictures release]]\nWhile in England, De Carlo recorded two singles, \"Say Goodbye\" and \"I Love a Man\".<ref>Studio Wants Larry Olivier to Co-Star with Ava Gardner: Looking at Hollywood.....\nHopper, Hedda. Chicago Daily Tribune 20 Apr 1951: b2.</ref> In March 1951 she signed a new contract with Universal to make one film a year for three years<ref>Hopper, Hedda. \"New Contract to Let Yvonne Travel: Looking at Hollywood\", ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', March 7, 1951, pg. A-14.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo went to Paramount to make a Western, ''[[Silver City (1951 film)|Silver City]]'' (1951) for producer Nat Holt, co-starring alongside [[Edmond O'Brien]] for a fee of $50,000.<ref>De Carlo p 156</ref>\n\nIn 1951,<ref>\"Yvonne De Carlo Pins Hopes for Future on Switch to Dramatic and Singing Roles\" Schuer, Philip K. ''Los Angeles Times'' 27 May 1951: D1.</ref><ref name=\"Slave Girl Wants Freedom\" /><ref name=\"Yvonne de Carlo Gets Hollywood Opera Role\">{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|authorlink1=Hedda Hopper|title=Yvonne de Carlo Gets Hollywood Opera Role|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1951/06/02/page/16/article/yvonne-de-carlo-gets-hollywood-opera-role/|accessdate=December 27, 2016|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 2, 1951}}</ref> De Carlo accepted an offer to open the thirtieth season of the [[Hollywood Bowl]] singing the [[breeches role]] of Prince Orlovsky in five performances of the opera ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' (''The Bat''), from July 10 to July 14.<ref>{{cite journal|title=63 to 86 Men For Hwd. Bowl Symph Series|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 14, 1951|page=12|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=157}} The performances were conducted by noted film composer [[Franz Waxman]]. In her autobiography she described her participation in ''Die Fledermaus'' as \"a rewarding experience, the aesthetic highlight of my life.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=157}}\n\nIn August 1951, De Carlo became the first American film star to visit the [[Israel|State of Israel]], giving concerts in [[Haifa]], [[Ramat Gan]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Jaffa]] which were exploited for propaganda purposes.<ref>\"Yvonne De Carlo Admits Serious Loves, but Chooses to Keep Them Mysterious\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', June 22, 1952, p. D1.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Harrison|first1=Scott|title=Actress Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://framework.latimes.com/2011/11/23/actress-yvonne-de-carlo|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> She drew capacity audiences and was \"royally received\" by the Israeli government and the public.<ref name=\"Jerusalem likes De Carlo\">{{cite news|title=Jerusalem likes De Carlo|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 19, 1951}}</ref> Her performances consisted of singing and dancing routines from her films.<ref name=\"Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East\">{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob|authorlink1=Bob Thomas (reporter)|title=Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/19627183|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=[[Moberly Monitor-Index]]|date=September 27, 1951}}</ref> Furthermore, she found that her films were extremely popular there, saying, \"Every time I played a concert, someone would yell, 'Sing something from ''[[Casbah (film)|Casbah]]''.'\"<ref name=\"Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East\"/> About the warm reception she received in Israel, she told columnist [[Louella Parsons]]:\n\n{{quote|Everyone in Israel was so wonderful to me, and I'll never forget the speech the Mayor of Jerusalem, Rabbi S. Z. Shragar, made. It had to be translated because he spoke in Hebrew. He is an orthodox Jew and lives up to his religion. He received me in his office and served me Turkish coffee, and I was told no woman had ever been invited to have coffee in his office before. He welcomed me to Israel in a gracious, kindly manner that I shall never forget. He gave me what they call a special blessing, not only for myself, but for all artists who were to come later.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parsons|first1=Louella|title=Tells Of Israel: Yvonne De Carlo Impressed By Reception In New Nation|work=Cumberland Sunday Times|date=November 25, 1951}}</ref>}}\n\nDe Carlo returned early from Tel Aviv to make ''[[The San Francisco Story]]'' (1952) with [[Joel McCrea]]. It was the first of a two-picture deal with Fidelity Pictures; the second was to be ''The Scarlet Flame'' about Brazil's battle for independence, which was never made.<ref>By THOMAS M PRYOR Special to The New York Times. (1951, Oct 13). FIDELITY TO FILM 'SCARLET FLAME'. New York Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/112132457</ref>\n\nShe made her live TV debut in \"Another Country\" for ''[[Lights Out (radio show)|Lights Out]]'' (1952). De Carlo wanted to make a film for [[Sydney Box]] called ''Queen of Sheba'' with [[Peter Ustinov]] as Solomon but it was never made.<ref>Drama: Yvonne De Carlo Named for British 'Sheba;' Find From 'Guys and Dolls' Set Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 21 Sep 1951: B9.</ref>\n\nShe went back to Universal for the first movie under her new contract, ''[[Scarlet Angel]]'' (1952) with [[Rock Hudson]].\n\nAt Paramount she did another film for Nat Holt, ''[[Hurricane Smith (1952 film)|Hurricane Smith]]'' (1952), then she appeared in \"Madame 44\" for ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'' (1952). She announced plans to form her own production company with her agent, Vancouver Productions.<ref>Looking at Hollywood: Yvonne De Carlo and Agent Form Own Movie Company Hopper, Hedda. ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' 5 Aug 1952: a2.</ref>  However, as she later wrote \"absolutely nothing\" came of this.<ref>De Carlo p 167</ref>\n\nDe Carlo went to MGM to make ''[[Sombrero (film)|Sombrero]]'' (1953), mostly shot in Mexico. She liked her character because it was \"almost madonnalike.It is a role that demands the most sincerity for its proper interpretation. Many pictures that I have done perhaps offered me typical outdoor parts or western, heroine parts. So long as I could convey a flashy sort of impression it was alright... I don't deny the importance of such parts for me. They are excellent. But is stands to reason that as one goes on one seeks less superficial assignments.<ref name=\"myst\">Yvonne De Carlo Admits Serious Loves, but Chooses to Keep Them Mysterious\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 22 June 1952: D1.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo was reunited with Hudson for ''[[Sea Devils (1953 film)|Sea Devils]]'' (1953), a Napoleonic adventure tale shot in Britain and France released through [[RKO]]. This meant she had to postpone a film she was going to make for [[Edward Small]], ''Savage Frontier''. She was offered a role in ''[[Innocents in Paris]]'' (1953) but ultimately did not appear in the film.<ref name=\"myst\"/>\n\nBack in the US she an adventure film set in the desert, ''[[Fort Algiers]]'' (1953),  for [[United Artists]], starring [[Carlos Thompson]], whom de Carlo had recommended.\n\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Alec Guinness in The Captain's Paradise.jpg|thumb|De Carlo with [[Alec Guinness]] in ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953)]]\nShe made her third film in Britain with the comedy ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953), as one of two wives a ship captain (played by [[Alec Guinness]]) keeps in separate ports. De Carlo played Nita, the sensual wife who lives in Morocco, while [[Celia Johnson]] played Maud, the demure wife who lives in Gibraltar. The film was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Story]], and ''The New York Times'' critic Bosley Crowther commended her performance by writing, \"And Miss De Carlo, as the siren, 'the mate of the tiger' in Mr. G. [Guinness], is wonderfully candid and suggestive of the hausfrau in every dame.\"<ref name=\"Captain's Paradise (1953) The Screen: New British Comedy Arrives; Alec Guinness Keeps Two Wives Happy in 'The Captain's Paradise' at Paris But Yvonne De Carlo and Celia Johnson Finally Cause the Downfall of Skipper\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Captain's Paradise (1953) The Screen: New British Comedy Arrives; Alec Guinness Keeps Two Wives Happy in 'The Captain's Paradise' at Paris But Yvonne De Carlo and Celia Johnson Finally Cause the Downfall of Skipper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F00EED71331E53BBC4151DFBF668388649EDE|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 29, 1953}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo made a fourth film in England, ''[[Happy Ever After (1954 film)|Happy Ever After]]'' (1954) with [[David Niven]], then was called back to the US do to a contemporary comedy on TV, ''[[The Backbone of America]]'' (1953) with [[Wendell Corey]]. In 1954, after the success of ''The Captain's Paradise,'' she expressed a desire to do more comedy:\n\n<blockquote>I've had my share of sirens and am happy to get away from them, no matter what the part. Just to look pretty on the screen as a romantic lead is probably all right, but \u2013 so what? I'd much rather do something in a good Western provided there's plenty of action. Action is what I like.<ref name=\"edwin\">\"Yvonne's Persistence Making Believers of Her Critics\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 2 May 1954: E1.</ref></blockquote>\n\nDe Carlo went back to Universal to make a Western with McCrea, ''[[Border River]]'' (1954), directed by Sherman. She went to Italy for ''[[The Contessa's Secret]]'' (1954) and returned to Hollywood for the independently produced ''[[Passion (1954 film)|Passion]]'' (1954). She wrote a 42-page treatment for a science-fiction film ''Operation Sram'', which was not made.<ref>Schallert, E. (1954, Jun 21). De mille gets vincent price as cruel builder; 'nightshade' on schedule. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/166630481</ref> De Carlo made the Western ''[[Shotgun (1955 film)|Shotgun]]'' (1955) with [[Sterling Hayden]] for Allied Artists. She did \"Hot Cargo\" for ''[[Screen Director's Playhouse]]'' (1956) with [[Rory Calhoun]] directed by [[Tay Garnett]].<ref>De Carlo Cover\nThe Washington Post and Times Herald (1954-1959); Washington, D.C. [Washington, D.C]01 Jan 1956: J1.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo made her third film for Universal under her new contract in ''[[Raw Edge (film)|Raw Edge]]'' (1956).  Republic starred her as [[Minna Planer|Minna Wagner]] in a biopic of [[Richard Wagner]], ''[[Magic Fire]]'' (1956). On TV she was in \"The Sainted General\" for ''[[Star Stage]]'' (1956). [[Republic Pictures|Republic]] reunited her with Duff in ''[[Flame of the Islands]]'' (1956), shot in the Bahamas.\n\n===''The Ten Commandments'' and last notable film roles (1954\u20131963)===\n[[File:Screenshot of Yvonne De Carlo in The Ten Commandments.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo as Sephora in ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)]]\nIn September 1954,<ref>{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo yesterday was cast by Cecil B. DeMille in the role of Sephora, Jethro's daughter and the shepherd girl who married Moses, in ''The Ten Commandments''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 15, 1954}}</ref> producer-director Cecil B. DeMille cast her as [[Zipporah]], the wife of Moses (played by [[Charlton Heston]]), in his biblical epic ''The Ten Commandments'', a [[Paramount Pictures]] production that premiered in November 1956. In his autobiography, DeMille explained he decided to cast De Carlo as Moses' wife after his casting director, Bert McKay, called his attention to one scene she played in ''Sombrero''. Even though the film \"was a picture far removed in theme from ''The Ten Commandments'',\" wrote DeMille, \"I sensed in her a depth, an emotional power, a womanly strength which the part of Sephora needed and which she gave it.\"<ref name=\"The autobiography of Cecil B. DeMille\">{{cite book|last=DeMille|first=Cecil Blount|title=The Autobiography of Cecil B. DeMille|year=1959|publisher=Prentice-Hall|page=416}}</ref>\n\nShe prepared extensively for the role, taking weaving lessons at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], and shepherding lessons in the [[San Fernando Valley]].{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}} Months before filming began, she had worked on the part with a drama coach.<ref name=\"Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne\">{{cite news|title=Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19580718&id=T3svAAAAIBAJ&pg=6984,3681522|accessdate=October 16, 2014|work=[[Deseret News|The Deseret News]]|date=July 18, 1958}}</ref> Her scenes were shot on Paramount's sound stages in 1955. Her performance received praise from critics. Crowther, the ''New York Times'' critic, was impressed: \"Yvonne DeCarlo as the Midianite shepherdess to whom Moses is wed is notably good in a severe role.\"<ref name=\"Movie Review: The Ten Commandments\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Movie Review: The Ten Commandments|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF1730A22CAA484CC1B7799A8E6896|accessdate=April 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 9, 1956}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that she \"is very fine as the simple Sephora,\"<ref>{{cite web|title='The Ten Commandments': Read THR's 1956 Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ten-commandments-1956-movie-review-754677|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[New York Daily News]]'' noticed that she \"plays the wife of Moses with conviction.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Flashback: Original 1956 review of 'The Ten Commandments' in the Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/flashback-stars-ten-commandment-article-1.2040699|website=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe fell in love with stuntman Bob Morgan while visiting the filming of ''The Ten Commandments'' in Egypt in 1954.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} They married in 1955, and their first son, Bruce, was born in 1956. DeMille became Bruce's godfather.{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}} Her second pregnancy meant she had to turn down the role of the female pirate DeMille had given her in his next production, ''[[The Buccaneer (1958 film)|The Buccaneer]]'' (1958).{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}}\n\nIt was announced she would team with [[Vittorio De Sica]] in an adaptation of ''[[The Baker's Wife]]'' to be shot in English and Italian<ref>Hopper, H. (1955, Jun 11). De carlo, de sica to do 'baker's wife'. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/166766450</ref> but the film was never made. Neither were two projects de Carlo was meant to make in Italy following ''Raw Edge'', ''The Mistress of Lebanon Castle'' with [[Trevor Howard]] and ''Honeymoon in Italy''.<ref>Drama: 'Something of Value' Bid DNow Centers on Travers; John Williams Resuming\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 22 Oct 1955: 13.</ref>\n\nInstead De Carlo co-starred with [[George Sanders]] and [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]] in ''[[Death of a Scoundrel]]'' (1956). ''The New York Times'' commended her performance as Bridget Kelly: \"Yvonne De Carlo does a solid and professional job as the adoring petty thief who rises to eminence with him [Sanders' character].\"<ref>{{cite web|title='Death of a Scoundrel' at Loew's State|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C06E7DB1230E23BBC4E53DFB767838D649EDE|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> On the small screen she was in \"Skits & Sketches\" for ''[[Shower of Stars]]'' (1957). She was also in ''[[Schlitz Playhouse]]'' (1957)\n\nDe Carlo released an [[LP record]] of standards called ''[[Yvonne De Carlo Sings]]'' on Masterseal Records, a subsidiary label of [[Remington Records]], in 1957. Orchestrated by future film composer [[John Williams]] under the pseudonym \"John Towner,\" the album contains ten tracks, \"End of a Love Affair\", \"[[In the Blue of Evening]]\", \"[[I Got It Bad (and That Ain't Good)]]\", \"[[Am I Blue?]]\", \"[[Little Girl Blue (song)|Little Girl Blue]]\", \"[[Blue Moon (1934 song)|Blue Moon]]\", \"[[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\", \"[[My Blue Heaven (song)|My Blue Heaven]]\", \"[[Mood Indigo]]\", \"[[One for My Baby (and One More for the Road)]]\".\n[[File:Yvonne de carlo - 1957.jpg|thumb|With [[Clark Gable]] in ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957)]]\nAs a result of the great success and positive reviews of ''The Ten Commandments'', De Carlo was offered lead roles in two [[Warner Bros.]] films that would be shot at the same time: ''[[The Helen Morgan Story]]'' and ''[[Band of Angels]]'', based on [[Robert Penn Warren]]'s novel. De Carlo chose the latter because her co-star would be [[Clark Gable]], one of her favorite actors.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=199}} The title refers to the short life expectancy of the black soldiers who fought with the Union troops in the Civil War, but the story is mainly about Amantha \"Manty\" Starr, a mixed-race [[Southern belle]] who is sold as a slave after her father's death and discovers that her deceased mother was a black slave on her father's plantation. Amantha is then taken to [[New Orleans]] where she is bought by plantation owner Hamish Bond (Gable), who falls in love with her. The film was both a critical and financial disappointment at the time of release.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=200}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Band of Angels (1957) - Notes|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/16194/Band-of-Angels/notes.html|website=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo was in \"Verdict of Three\" for ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' (1958). She made a [[French Foreign Legion]] movie with [[Victor Mature]], ''[[Timbuktu (1959 film)|Timbuktu]],'' directed by [[Jacques Tourneur]] (1958). She unsuccessfully auditioned for the Broadway musical ''[[Destry Rides Again (musical)|Destry Rides Again]]'' losing out to [[Dolores Gray]].<ref>De Carlo p 202</ref>\n\nIn May 1958,<ref name=\"De Carlo Signed for Italian 'Magdalene'\">{{cite news|title=De Carlo Signed for Italian 'Magdalene'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 20, 1958}}</ref> De Carlo was signed to play [[Mary Magdalene]] in the Italian biblical epic ''[[The Sword and the Cross]]'' (tentatively titled ''The Great Sinner'' and released in the United States as ''Mary Magdalene''), with [[Jorge Mistral]] as her love interest, the Roman Gaius Marcellus, and [[Rossana Podest\u00e0]] as her sister, Martha. The film's director, [[Carlo Ludovico Bragaglia]], later remembered that \"producer, Ottavio Poggi, had sent the provisional script to America, so Yvonne De Carlo could read it and decide on her participation in the film. She read it and got very excited, agreeing to play the role of Magdalene.\"<ref name=\"Nato col cinema\">{{cite book|last1=Antonelli|first1=Lamberto|last2=Laura|first2=Ernesto G.|title=Nato col cinema: Carlo Ludovico Braggalia: cent'anni tra arti e cinema|date=1992|publisher=A.N.C.C.I.|page=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rmxZAAAAMAAJ&dq=Lei+lo+lesse+e+se+ne+entusiasm%C3%B2+moltissimo%2C+accettando+di+interpretare+il+ruolo&q=Yvonne+De+Carlo|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The film was shot in English and later dubbed in Italian.<ref name=\"Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne\" />\n\nDe Carlo put together a nightclub act and toured with it in South America. She guest starred on ''[[Bonanza]]'' (\"A Rose for Lotta\", 1959), ''[[Adventures in Paradise (TV series)|Adventures in Paradise]]'' (\"Isle of Eden\", 1960), ''[[Death Valley Days]]'' (\"The Lady Was an M.D\", 1961), ''[[Follow the Sun (TV series)|Follow the Sun]]'' (\"The Longest Crap Game in History\" [1961] and \"Annie Beeler's Place\", 1962) and ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]'' (\"Who Killed Beau Sparrow?\", 1963). She also played ''Destry Rides Again'' in summer stock.\n[[File:John Wayne-Yvonne De Carlo in McLintock!.jpg|thumb|left|With [[John Wayne]] in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963)]]\nDe Carlo's husband had been permanently crippled while working as a stunt man on ''[[How the West Was Won (film)|How the West Was Won]]'' (1963), eventually losing his leg. De Carlo took any job going, appearing in night club acts across the country as well as a play in stock, ''Third Best Sport''.\n\nTo help out, [[John Wayne]] offered her the supporting role of Louise Warren, the title character's cook in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963), with Wayne and [[Maureen O'Hara]]. She was second billed in a Western ''[[Law of the Lawless]]'' (1964) and played the Spanish dancer Dolores in the [[Bob Hope]] comedy ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964).\n\nDe Carlo was in \"The Night the Monkey Died\" for ''[[The Greatest Show on Earth (TV series)|The Greatest Show on Earth]]'' (1964). She took over a role on ''[[Enter Laughing]]'' on Broadway for a week, and played in it when the production went on tour.\n\n==Later Career==\n===''The Munsters'' (1964\u20131966)===\n[[File:Lily.Munster.jpg|thumb|right|Publicity photo of De Carlo as [[Lily Munster]]]]\nShe was in debt by 1964 when she signed a contract with [[Universal Studios]] to perform the female lead role in ''[[The Munsters]]'' opposite [[Fred Gwynne]]. She was also the producers' choice to play [[Lily Munster]] when [[Joan Marshall]], who played the character (originally called \"Phoebe\"), was dropped from consideration for the role. When De Carlo was asked how a glamorous actress could succeed as a ghoulish matriarch of a haunted house, she replied simply, \"I follow the directions I received on the first day of shooting: 'Play her just like ''[[The Donna Reed Show|Donna Reed]]''.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5fcgAAAAIBAJ&pg=1176,787858&dq=john+astin&hl=en|title=The Day \u2013 Google News Archive|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> She sang and played the [[harp]] in at least one episode (\"Far Out Munsters\") of ''The Munsters''.\n\nAfter the show's cancellation, she reprised her role as Lily Munster in the [[Technicolor]] film ''[[Munster, Go Home!]]'' (1966), partially in hopes of renewing interest in the sitcom. Despite the attempt, ''The Munsters'' was cancelled after 70 episodes. Of the sitcom and its cast and crew, she said: \"It was a happy show with audience appeal for both children and adults. It was a happy show behind the scenes, too; we all enjoy working with each other.\"<ref name=\"Monstrous Mayor\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Erskine|title=Monstrous Mayor|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19660424&id=JGocAAAAIBAJ&pg=5514,4038787|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=April 24, 1966}}</ref> Years later, in 1987, she said: \"I think Yvonne De Carlo was more famous than Lily, but I gained the younger audience through ''The Munsters''. And it was a steady job.\"<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo Enjoys 'Munsters' Rebirth\">{{cite news|last1=Oricchio|first1=Michael|title=Yvonne DeCarlo Enjoys 'Munsters' Rebirth|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19870530&id=bMFPAAAAIBAJ&pg=5401,8081705|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=[[Star-Banner|Ocala Star-Banner]]|date=May 30, 1987}}</ref>\n\n===Stage work and ''Follies'' (1967\u20131973)===\nAfter ''The Munsters'', she guest starred in \"The Moulin Ruse Affair\" in ''[[The Girl from UNCLE]]'' (1967) and \"The Raiders\" for ''[[Custer]]'' (1967) and episodes of ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''.\n\nShe starred in ''[[Hostile Guns]]'' (1967) and ''[[Arizona Bushwhackers]]'' (1968), a pair of low-budget westerns produced by [[A. C. Lyles]] and released by Paramount Pictures. During this time, she also had a supporting role in the 1968 thriller ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]''.\n\nAfter 1967, De Carlo became increasingly active in musicals, appearing in off-Broadway productions of ''[[Pal Joey (musical)|Pal Joey]]'' and ''Catch Me If You Can''. In early 1968 she joined [[Donald O'Connor]] in a 15-week run of ''[[Little Me (musical)|Little Me]]'' staged between Lake Tahoe and Las Vegas and she did a five-month tour in ''[[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|Hello Dolly]]''. Later she toured in ''[[Cactus Flower (play)|Cactus Flower]]''.<ref name=\"De Carlo 1987\">{{cite book|last=De Carlo|first=Yvonne|author2=Warren, Doug|title=Yvonne: An Autobiography|year=1987|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9780312002176|url=https://archive.org/details/yvonneautobiogra00deca_0}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo continued to appear in films such as ''[[The Delta Factor (film)|The Delta Factor]]'' (1970) and had a notable part in [[Russ Meyer]]'s ''[[The Seven Minutes (film)|The Seven Minutes]]'' (1971). The ''Los Angeles Times'' said about the latter that De Carlo featured in \"an improbable sequence pulled off with verve by the still glamorous star.\"<ref>Thomas, K. (1971, Sep 08). 'Seven' attacks censorship. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/156863129</ref>\n\nHer defining stage role was as \"Carlotta Campion\" in [[Harold Prince]]'s production of the [[Stephen Sondheim]] musical ''[[Follies]]'' in 1971-72.<ref name = \"De Carlo 1987\"/> Playing a washed-up star at a reunion of old theater colleagues, she introduced the song \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\".{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=140}} De Carlo says she was told the part was written especially for her.<ref>De Carlo p 216</ref>\n\nIn October 1972, De Carlo arrived in [[Australia]] to replace [[Cyd Charisse]] in [[Edgley International|Michael Edgley]]'s production of ''[[No, No, Nanette]]''.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=226}} Her opening night was on November 6, 1972 at [[Her Majesty's Theatre, Melbourne|Her Majesty's Theatre]] in [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo\" /> The show moved on to [[Adelaide]],{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=229}} [[Sydney]], and then to several [[New Zealand]] cities.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=231}} It closed in the fall of 1973, and De Carlo returned to the United States.\n\nIn late 1973 and early 1974, she starred in a production of [[Ben Bagley]]'s ''Decline and Fall of the Entire World as Seen Through the Eyes of Cole Porter'' in San Diego.\n\nIn May 1975, she starred in the San Bernardino Civic Light Opera's production of ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]'' at the [[California Theatre (San Bernardino)|California Theatre of the Performing Arts]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=233}} ''[[The San Bernardino Sun]]'' described her performance as \"brilliant\" and wrote, \"a packed house watched Yvonne De Carlo give a new dimension to Margo Channing, a part she was playing for the first time, but nonetheless, a part she was very well suited for.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Jimmy|title=Yvonne DeCarlo brilliant in 'Applause'|work=The Sun-Telegram|date=May 11, 1975|page=D-6}}</ref>\n\n===Later career (1974\u20131995)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo (1979).jpg|thumb|200px|right|De Carlo at the National Film Society convention, May 1979]]\nDe Carlo appeared in ''[[The Girl on the Late, Late Show]]'' (1974), ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1974 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1974), ''[[Arizona Slim]]'' (1974), ''[[The Intruder (1975 film)|The Intruder]]'' (1975), ''[[Blazing Stewardesses]]'' (1975), ''[[It Seemed Like a Good Idea at the Time]]'' (1975), ''[[Black Fire (film)|Black Fire]]'' (1975), and ''[[La casa de las sombras]]'' (1976).\n\nShe continued to appear on stage, notably in ''Dames at Sea'', ''Barefoot in the Park'' and ''The Sound of Music''.\n\nShe was seen on ''[[Satan's Cheerleaders]]'' (1977), ''[[Nocturna (1979 film)|Nocturna]]'' (1979), ''[[Guyana: Cult of the Damned]]'' (1979), ''[[Fuego negro]]'' (1979), ''[[The Silent Scream (1979 film)|The Silent Scream]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Man with Bogart's Face ]]'' (1980). She guest starred on shows like ''[[Fantasy Island]]''.\n\nDe Carlo was in ''[[The Munsters' Revenge]]'' (1981), then ''[[Liar's Moon]]'' (1982), ''[[Play Dead (1981 film)|Play Dead]]'' (1982), ''Vultures'' (1984), ''[[Flesh and Bullets]]'' (1985), and ''[[A Masterpiece of Murder]]'' (1986) (with [[Bob Hope]]). She was in a revival of ''The Munsters''.\n\nDe Carlo's later films included ''[[American Gothic (1988 film)|American Gothic]]'' (1988), for which she won the Best Actress Award from [[Fantafestival|International Science Fiction and Fantasy Film Show (Fantafestival)]]; ''[[Cellar Dweller]]'' (1988); and ''[[Mirror, Mirror (1990 film)|Mirror Mirror]]'' (1990). She had a supporting role as the title character's Aunt Rosa in the [[Sylvester Stallone]] comedy ''[[Oscar (1991 film)|Oscar]]'' (1991). Aunt Rosa is present when Oscar's father, played by [[Kirk Douglas]], extracts \"a deathbed promise\" from his son. Of her role, De Carlo said, \"Mine is a small part&mdash;but funny.\"<ref name=\"In Search of ... Yvonne De Carlo\">{{cite news|last1=Broeske|first1=Pat H.|title=In Search of ... Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/entertainment/ca-155_1_carlo-yvonne-tv|accessdate=January 22, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 13, 1991}}</ref>\n\nShe was in ''[[The Naked Truth (1992 film)|The Naked Truth]]'' (1992), ''[[Seasons of the Heart (1993 film)|Seasons of the Heart]]'' (1993), and \"Death of Some Salesmen\" in ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'' (1993). She had a small cameo role in ''[[Here Come the Munsters]]'', a 1995 television film remake of ''The Munsters''. De Carlo, along with [[Al Lewis (actor)|Al Lewis]], [[Pat Priest (actress)|Pat Priest]], and [[Butch Patrick]], did not have to wear costumes \"because the Munsters have several lives.\"<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\">{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Susan|title=No Monkey Business : YVONNE DE CARLO TAKES ON ABC'S REMAKE OF 'THE BAREFOOT EXECUTIVE'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-05/news/tv-64921_1_barefoot-executive|accessdate=March 31, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 5, 1995}}</ref>\n\nHer final performance was as Norma, \"an eccentric [[Norma Desmond]] lookalike,\" in the 1995 television film ''[[The Barefoot Executive]]'', a [[Disney Channel]] remake of the [[The Barefoot Executive|1971 film of the same title]].<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\" /> Norma, a former [[stand-in]] for film actors, \"monkey-sits\" the title character, a chimpanzee named Archie who is able to predict top-rated television series. \"She has these outrageous costumes&mdash;six of them&mdash;and it's just a small part,\" De Carlo told ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. \"But I like to do small things now.\"<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\" />\n\nIn 2007, her son Bruce revealed that, before her death, she played supporting roles in two independent films that have yet to be released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spiegelman|first1=Arthur|title=\"Munsters\" actress Yvonne De Carlo dies at 84|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-decarlo/munsters-actress-yvonne-de-carlo-dies-at-84-idUSN1030669220070111|accessdate=March 31, 2018|work=[[Reuters]]|date=January 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1950, De Carlo purchased an eleven-room ranch house on five-and-a-half acres of \"hilly woodland\" on [[Coldwater Canyon Avenue|Coldwater Canyon Drive]]{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=151}} in [[Studio City, Los Angeles]], above [[Beverly Hills]]. De Carlo described it as her \"dream home\" and hired an architect to help her design \"an English-style dining room, with paneling and stained-glass windows.\" She also built stables for her horses{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} and a large swimming pool.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carrol|first1=Lee|title=Shirley Temple ambitious for daughter|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/51595749?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+beverly+hills|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]|date=June 10, 1950}}</ref> She sold the property in 1975.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beale|first1=Lauren|title=Yvonne de Carlo's old compound in Studio City is listed|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/08/home/la-hm-hotprop-yvonne-de-carlo-20110208|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, she moved to a ranch in the [[Santa Ynez Valley]],{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=239}} near [[Solvang]], [[California]].\n\n===Relationships===\nDe Carlo's name was linked with a number of famous men through her career, including [[Howard Hughes]]<ref name=\"NYTobit\" /> and [[Robert Stack]]. It is claimed that she had affairs with [[Mohammad Reza Shah]] of Iran during the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=KINZER |first1=STEPHEN |title=All the Shah's men : an American coup and the roots of Middle East terror |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |isbn=0-471-26517-9 |page=62 |accessdate=|date=2003-06-27 }}</ref>. In 1947, she announced her engagement to actor [[Howard Duff]],<ref>\"Screen Lovers to Be Married\" ''Los Angeles Times,'' April 30, 1947, pg. 7.</ref> her co-star in ''Brute Force'' (1947) and ''Calamity Jane and Sam Bass'' (1949),  but they never married. She was engaged four more times&mdash;to Canadian businessman Gordon Noel, American stuntman [[Jock Mahoney]], English photographer [[Cornel Lucas]], and Scottish actor [[Robert Urquhart (actor)|Richard Urquhart]]&mdash;but felt \"trapped\" whenever she looked at the engagement ring on her finger.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=93}} While engaged to Mahoney, De Carlo became pregnant and also discovered she had a large [[ovarian cyst]]. The tumor was surgically removed and, as a result, she lost the baby.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=144}} Her relationship with Mahoney ended when De Carlo found out he was seeing another woman, actress [[Margaret Field]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=152}}\n\nIn 1954, she told a journalist:\n\n<blockquote>I think it is wonderful to work. I dedicate more time now than ever to study. I really like to delve deeply into the characters and the stories in order to make the most of each part I play. It seems best to remain free of any serious romantic attachments under these circumstances. I will have to meet an exceptional and understanding person, indeed, before I think of marriage. I haven't met such a person yet.<ref name=\"edwin\"/></blockquote>\n\n===Marriage===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Bob Morgan at the New York premiere of The Ten Commandments.JPG|thumb|De Carlo with her husband, Robert Morgan, at the New York premiere of ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)]]\nDe Carlo met [[stunt performer|stuntman]] Robert Drew \"Bob\" Morgan (1915\u20131999) on the set of ''Shotgun'' in 1955, but he was married and had a child, daughter Bari Lee (b. 1947),<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~houghtonfamily/Morgan/p12.htm Profile], genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com; accessed June 21, 2016.</ref> and De Carlo had \"no intention of causing that marriage to break up.\"{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=134}} However, they met again, after the death of Morgan's wife, on the set of ''The Ten Commandments'' in Egypt,<ref name=\"She's A Happy Homebody! Marriage, Motherhood Curb Yvonne's Urge to Travel\">{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|authorlink1=Hedda Hopper|title=She's A Happy Homebody! Marriage, Motherhood Curb Yvonne's Urge to Travel|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1956/12/30/page/124/article/shes-a-happy-homebody|accessdate=January 5, 2017|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=December 30, 1956}}</ref> where they \"seemed immediately attracted to each other.\"{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} They were married on November 21, 1955, at St. Stephen's Episcopal Church in [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref name=\"Most Glamorous Spinster Loses Title in Reno; Hollywood Actress Weds in Quiet Ceremony\">{{cite news|title=Most Glamorous Spinster Loses Title in Reno; Hollywood Actress Weds in Quiet Ceremony|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/79190405/|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=Nevada State Journal|date=November 22, 1955}}</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,893252,00.html Profile], ''Time Magazine''; accessed June 21, 2016.</ref> De Carlo raised Bari as her own and had two sons with Morgan: Bruce Ross (b. 1956), whose godfather was [[Cecil B. DeMille]];{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}}{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=84}} and Michael (1957\u20131997).\n\nMorgan lost his left leg after being run over by a train while filming ''[[How the West Was Won (film)|How the West Was Won]]'' (1962). However, his contract with [[MGM]] assumed no responsibility for the accident. De Carlo and Morgan filed a $1.4 million lawsuit against the studio, claiming her husband was permanently disabled. They divorced in July 1973.<ref name=\"California Divorce Index\">{{cite web|title=Peggy Y Middleton - California Divorce Index|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPRV-DPC|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nDe Carlo, a [[United States nationality law|naturalized citizen]] of the United States, was an active [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] who campaigned for [[Richard Nixon]],<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo A Star Reborn\">{{cite news|last1=Christy|first1=Marian|title=Yvonne DeCarlo A Star Reborn|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19720712&id=7JMjAAAAIBAJ&pg=6095,798572&hl=en|accessdate=August 18, 2015|work=[[Reading Eagle]]|agency=United Feature Syndicate|date=July 12, 1972}}</ref> [[Ronald Reagan]]<ref>\"Southland Observations: There's No Business Like Politics\" Kerby, Phil. ''Los Angeles Times'', August 12, 1976, pg. D1.</ref> and [[Gerald Ford]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schwartzenberg|first1=Roger-G\u00e9rard|title=The Superstar Show of Government|date=1980|publisher=[[Barron's Educational Series]]|isbn=9780812052589|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f_ocAAAAIAAJ&dq=yvonne+de+carlo+supporter+gerald+ford&q=Yvonne+de+Carlo|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[Conservatism|conservative]], she stated half-jokingly in a 1976 television interview: \"I'm all for men and I think they ought to stay up there and be the bosses, and have women wait on them hand and foot and put their slippers on and hand them the pipe and serve seven course meals; as long as they open the door, support the woman, and do their duty in the bedroom, et cetera.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo on feminism, equal rights & Hollywood, 1976|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p9vDKRQMk5s|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nDe Carlo's maternal grandparents came from distinct religious backgrounds: He was [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and she was [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=19}} They raised her as an [[Anglican]]; she was a member and chorister of Vancouver's [[St. Paul's Anglican Church (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Anglican Church]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=122}}\n\nIn her autobiography, De Carlo wrote about her faith in God: \"God has saved me and mine from some pretty sticky situations. For me, religion is a little like being a Republican or a Democrat. It's not the party that counts, it's the man. Therefore, I care not what house of worship I enter, be it Catholic, Presbyterian, or Baptist. I elected God a long time ago and I'll stick with Him, because I don't think His term will ever be up.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=239}}\n\n==Death==\nDe Carlo suffered a minor [[stroke]] in 1998. She later became a resident of the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]], in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]], where she spent her last years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/11/arts/television/11decarlo.html|title=Yvonne De Carlo - The Munsters - Obituary|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=2007-01-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She died from [[heart failure]] on January 8, 2007, and was cremated.<ref name=NYTobit>{{cite news|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|title=Yvonne De Carlo Dies at 84; Played Lily on 'Munsters'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/11/arts/television/11decarlo.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 11, 2007|page=B6}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* In 1946, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named her one of the three \"top new Hollywood stars\" of 1945, along with [[Lizabeth Scott]] and [[Lauren Bacall]]: \"Miss de Carlo is definitely a personality. She has proved this in Universal's ''Salome, Where She Danced'', and followed this appearance as star in [the] same company's ''Frontier Gal''. She is a controversial figure, but she's managed to come out a star during discussions.\"<ref name=\"Lizabeth Scott, Bacall, de Carlo Top New Hollywood Stars A-Blooming\">{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Whitney|title=Lizabeth Scott, Bacall, de Carlo Top New Hollywood Stars A-Blooming|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 9, 1946|volume=161|issue=5|pages=3, 68|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety161-1946-01#page/n49/mode/2up/search/de+carlo|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* She was a medalist in ''[[Boxoffice (magazine)|Boxoffice Barometer]]'''s The All-American Screen Favorites of 1946 list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The All-American Screen Favorites of 1946|journal=Boxoffice Barometer|date=November 9, 1946|page=18\u2013A|url=https://archive.org/stream/boxofficebaromet00boxo_3#page/n17/mode/2up/search/yvonne|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* She was a medalist in ''Boxoffice Barometer'''s The All-American Screen Favorites of 1947 list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The All-American Screen Favorites of 1947|journal=Boxoffice Barometer|date=November 15, 1947|page=19|url=https://archive.org/stream/boxofficebaromet00boxo_4#page/n17/mode/2up/search/yvonne+de+carlo|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* In 1947, [[Max Factor]]'s chief hair stylist, Fred Fredericks, named her one of the 10 \"best tressed\" film actresses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gives 'Best Tressed' Film Stars|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/127077723?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+tressed|accessdate=April 5, 2018|work=News|date=January 22, 1947}}</ref>\n* In 1950, the Camera Club of America voted her \"Sexnicolor Queen of the Screen\" \"for putting more sex [appeal] into [[Technicolor]] than any other star.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM BRIEFS - Queen Yvonne|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18487164?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+queen+technicolor|accessdate=April 5, 2018|work=[[The Sun-Herald|The Sunday Herald]]|date=December 10, 1950}}</ref>\n* In 1957, she received a BoxOffice Blue Ribbon Award for ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956).<ref name=\"Boxoffice Blue Ribbon Awards\">{{cite web|title=Recipients of Two or More Awards From March 1932, Through August 1965 Are Herein Cited|url=http://www.astortheater.org/articles20.html|website=Astor Theater|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* In 1960, she was awarded two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. The motion picture star is on the south side of the 6100 block of Hollywood Boulevard. The television star is on the north side of the 6700 block of Hollywood Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo - Hollywood Star Walk - Los Angeles Times|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/yvonne-de-carlo/|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* In 1964, she received a second BoxOffice Blue Ribbon Award for ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963).<ref name=\"Boxoffice Blue Ribbon Awards\" />\n* In 1966, she was honored by the [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|City of Niagara Falls, Canada]], for \"having created good will for her native country and given inspiration to others.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In Hollywood - Yvonne Honored|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=DS19660521.2.31&txq=yvonne+de+carlo+honored|accessdate=April 6, 2018|work=[[The Desert Sun|Desert Sun]]|agency=UPI|date=May 21, 1966}}</ref>\n* In 1966, she was named honorary mayor of [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Monstrous Mayor\" />\n* In 1987, she won the [[Fantafestival|International Science Fiction and Fantasy Film Show (Fantafestival) Award]] for Best Actress for ''[[American Gothic (1988 film)|American Gothic]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grazzini|first1=Giovanni|title=Cinema|date=1987|publisher=Ed. Laterza|isbn=9788842030300|page=213}}</ref>\n* In 2005, she was one of the 250 female Hollywood legends nominated for the [[American Film Institute]]'s [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Stars|100 Years ... 100 Stars]] list.<ref>{{cite web |title=America's Greatest Legends \u2013 A compendium of the 500 stars nominated for top 50 \"Greatest Screen Legends\" status. |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100years/stars500.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2007, she was nominated for the \"Who Knew They Could Sing?\" [[TV Land Award]] for ''[[The Munsters]]''.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In the 1954 ''[[I Love Lucy]]'' episode \"Ricky's Screen Test\", Lucy reads in a newspaper that MGM is considering several Hollywood actresses, including Yvonne De Carlo, for the female lead role in Ricky's film ''Don Juan''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Monush |first1=Barry |last2=Sheridan |first2=James |title=Lucille Ball FAQ: Everything Left to Know About America's Favorite Redhead |date=2011 |publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vq2Zff8JZZ8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9781557839336 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Yvonne De Carlo filmography}}\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles===\n* \"I Love a Man\" / \"Say Goodbye\" ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]], 1950)<ref>{{cite web|title=78 RPM - Yvonne De Carlo - Say Goodbye / I Love A Man - Columbia - UK - DB.2850|url=http://www.45worlds.com/78rpm/record/db2850|website=45worlds|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"Take It Or Leave It\" / \"Three Little Stars\" ([[Capitol Records|Capitol]], 1955)<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo - Take It Or Leave It / Three Little Stars - Capitol - USA - F3206|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/f3206|website=45cat|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"That's Love\" / \"The Secret of Love\" ([[Imperial Records|Imperial]], 1957)<ref name=\"Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'\">{{cite web|title=Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'|url=http://honkingduck.com/discography/artist/yvonne_de_carlo|website=The Honking Duck|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"I Would Give My Heart\" / \"Rockin' In The Orbit\" (Imperial, 1958)<ref name=\"Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'\" />\n\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Yvonne De Carlo Sings]]'' (Masterseal, 1957)\n\n===Duets===\n* \"[[You Belong to My Heart]]\" with [[Bill Lee (singer)|Bill Lee]] (included in ''That's Entertainment! The Ultimate Anthology of M-G-M Musicals'')<ref>{{cite web|title=That's Entertainment! The Ultimate Anthology of M-G-M Musicals [Rhino Box Set]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thats-entertainment%21-the-ultimate-anthology-of-m-g-m-musicals-rhino-box-set-mw0000723726|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"[[Getting to Know You (song)|Getting to Know You]]\" with [[Frank Sinatra]] (included in ''The Frank Sinatra Duets'')<ref>{{cite web|title=The Frank Sinatra Duets|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/comp/frank-sinatra/the-frank-sinatra-duets-1/|website=[[Rate Your Music]]|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Bawden|first1=James|last2=Miller|first2=Ron|chapter=Yvonne De Carlo|title=You Ain't Heard Nothin' Yet: Interviews with Stars from Hollywood's Golden Era|year=2017|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|isbn=9780813174235|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=De Carlo|first1=Yvonne|last2=Warren|first2=Doug|title=Yvonne: An Autobiography|year=1987|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|isbn=9780312002176|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/yvonneautobiogra00deca_0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foster|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Foster (writer)|chapter=Yvonne De Carlo|title=Once Upon a Time in Paradise: Canadians in the Golden Age of Hollywood|year=2003|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|isbn=9781459712676|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Orrison|first=Katherine|authorlink=Katherine Orrison|chapter=Mrs. Moses: Yvonne De Carlo|title=Written in Stone: Making Cecil B. DeMille's Epic The Ten Commandments|year=1999|publisher=Vestal Press|isbn=9781461734819|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nick|chapter=Bruce Morgan on Yvonne De Carlo|title=Raised by the Stars: Interviews with 29 Children of Hollywood Actors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yImkNboc4tsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2011|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|isbn=978-0-7864-6403-6|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|Television|Music}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons}}\n<!-- * {{Official website|http://www.officialyvonnedecarlo.com}} -->\n* {{webarchive |title= Official website |date= January 4, 2013 |url= https://archive.is/20130104063929/www.officialyvonnedecarlo.com/}} \n* {{IMDb name|1119}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://archive.org/details/LampOfMemory |title= Lamp Of Memory |date= 1944 |work= Soundie |accessdate= Sep 16, 2016 |format= Video clip }} {{cite web |url= https://archive.org/details/prelinger |title= Prelinger Archive  }}\nObituaries:\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/11/arts/television/11decarlo.html  |series= Obituary |newspaper= NY Times |accessdate= Sep 16, 2016 |date= Jan 11, 2007 |title= Yvonne De Carlo, Who Played Lily on 'The Munsters,' Dies at 84 }}\n* {{cite web |publisher= Media Newswire |series= Press release |url= http://media-newswire.com/release_1040947.html |title= Munsters' Television Star Yvonne de Carlo Dies at 84 |accessdate= Sep 16, 2016 |date= Jan 11, 2007 }}\n* {{cite news |title= Yvonne de Carlo |series= Obituary |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=Jan 12, 2007 |location=London, UK |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1539222/Yvonne-de-Carlo.html |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090213190759/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1539222/Yvonne-de-Carlo.html |archivedate= February 13, 2009 }} \n* {{cite web |url= http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/1976/yvonne-de-carlo |title= Yvonne De Carlo |website= Virtual History |accessdate= Sep 16, 2016 }}\n* {{Find a Grave|17377818}}\n\n{{Burlesque Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Carlo, Yvonne}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Actresses of British descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Canadian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Canadian musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Canadian television personalities]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Imperial Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:People deported from the United States]] <!-- see text -->\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) film actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian-American actress, dancer, and singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Yvonne De Carlo\n| image      = YvonneDC.jpg\n| caption    = De Carlo c. 1950s\n| birth_name  = Margaret Yvonne Middleton\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1922|9|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2007|1|8|1922|9|1|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actress, dancer, singer\n| years_active = 1939\u20131995\n| notable_works = [[Zipporah|Sephora]] from [[Cecil B. DeMille]]'s ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)\n| television = ''[[The Munsters]]'' (1964\u20131966)\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Robert Drew Morgan|1955|1973|end=div}}\n| children = 2\n| module     = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| instrument = Vocals\n| genre = {{Flat list|\n* [[Blues]]\n* [[jazz]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| label = {{Flat list|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Imperial Records|Imperial]]\n* Masterseal ([[Remington Records|Remington]])\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Yvonne De Carlo''' (born '''Margaret Yvonne Middleton'''; September 1, 1922 \u2013 January 8, 2007) was a [[Canadian]]-American actress, dancer, and singer. A brunette with blue-grey eyes, she became an internationally famous [[Hollywood]] film star in the [[1940s in film|1940s]] and [[1950s in film|1950s]], made several recordings, and later acted on television and stage.\n\nBorn in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], De Carlo was raised in the home of her Presbyterian maternal grandparents. Her mother enrolled her in a local dance school when she was three. By the early 1940s, she and her mother had moved to Los Angeles, where De Carlo participated in beauty contests and worked as a dancer in nightclubs.\n\nShe began working in motion pictures in 1941, in short subjects. She sang \"The Lamp of Memory\" in a three-minute [[Soundies]] musical, and worked briefly at [[Columbia Pictures]]. In 1942, she signed a three-year contract with [[Paramount Pictures]], where she was given uncredited bit parts in important films and was intended to replace [[Dorothy Lamour]]. Her first lead was for independent producer [[E. B. Derr]] in the [[James Fenimore Cooper]] adventure ''[[The Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]'' (1943, ultimately released by [[Republic Pictures]]).\n\nShe obtained her breakthrough role in ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945), a [[Universal Pictures]] release produced by [[Walter Wanger]], who described her as \"the most beautiful girl in the world.\"<ref name=\"Most Beautiful Girl Discovered'\">{{cite news|title=\"Most Beautiful Girl\" Discovered|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1338&dat=19440918&id=a91YAAAAIBAJ&pg=5975,3223468|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]]|date=September 18, 1944}}</ref><ref name=\"Salome, Where She Danced Comes to Harris'\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Harold V.|title=\"Salome, Where She Danced\" Comes to Harris|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19450507&id=bbhRAAAAIBAJ&pg=3004,542086|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=May 7, 1945}}</ref><ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'\">{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19450725&id=Mb4tAAAAIBAJ&pg=4893,3527502|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|date=July 25, 1945}}</ref> The film's publicity and success turned her into a star, and she signed a five-year contract with Universal. From then on, Universal starred her in its lavish Technicolor productions, such as ''[[Frontier Gal]]'' (1945), ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947), and ''[[Slave Girl (film)|Slave Girl]]'' (1947). Cameramen voted her \"Queen of Technicolor\" three years in a row.<ref name=\"Slave Girl Wants Freedom\">{{cite news|last=Willett|first=Bob|title=Slave Girl Wants Freedom: Tired of playing exotic sirens, Canada's lovely Yvonne De Carlo seeks more serious film roles|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19541113&id=YPkwAAAAIBAJ&pg=5353,3064717|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=November 13, 1954}}</ref> Tired of being typecast as exotic women, she made her first serious dramatic performances in two [[film noir|films noir]], ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947) and ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949).\n\nThe first American film star to visit [[Israel]], De Carlo received further recognition as an actress for her work in the British comedies ''[[Hotel Sahara]]'' (1951) and ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953). Her career reached its peak when eminent producer-director [[Cecil B. DeMille]] cast her as [[Moses]]' [[Midian]]ite wife, [[Zipporah|Sephora]], her most prominent role, in his biblical epic ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956),<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2008\">{{cite book|last=Jacob Sparks|first=Karen|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=2008|isbn=9781593394257|page=123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wKvMZWcgKYC&dq=cecil+b+demille+yvonne+de+carlo&q=Yvonne+De+Carlo}}</ref> which was immensely successful at the box office and remains an annual tradition on television. Her success continued with starring roles in ''[[Flame of the Islands]]'' (1956), ''[[Death of a Scoundrel]]'' (1956), ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957), and ''[[The Sword and the Cross]]'' (1958), in which she portrayed [[Mary Magdalene]]. She also accepted supporting roles in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963) and ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964).\n\nShe gained a new generation of fans as a star of the CBS sitcom ''[[The Munsters]]'' (1964\u20131966),<ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Is The Mama In a Nice Monster Family\">{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo Is The Mama In a Nice Monster Family|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19640623&id=nWJSAAAAIBAJ&pg=5511,1718564|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=June 23, 1964}}</ref> playing [[Herman Munster]]'s glamorous [[vampire]] wife, [[Lily Munster|Lily]], a role she reprised in the feature film ''[[Munster, Go Home!]]'' (1966) and the television film ''[[The Munsters' Revenge]]'' (1981). In 1971, she played Carlotta Campion and introduced the popular song \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\" in the Broadway production of the [[Stephen Sondheim]] musical ''[[Follies]]''. ''Yvonne'', her best-selling autobiography, was published in 1987. A stroke survivor, De Carlo died of heart failure in 2007. She was awarded two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] for her contributions to motion pictures and television.\n\n==Early life==\n{{quote box\n |class = <!-- Advanced users only.  See the \"Custom classes\" section below. -->\n |title = \n |quote = On the evening of August 31 that year [1922], three days after her own birthday, Marie was having five-minute contractions. She was taken to the public ward of St. Paul's Hospital, where she went through a difficult labor. I was born the following morning amid the tumult of the season's worst thunderstorm. Marie's doctor hadn't arrived, and the delivery was made by a pair of floor nurses. They confirmed afterward that as she was being shifted to the delivery table, she was shouting, \"I want a girl. It must be a girl. I want a dancer!\"\n |author = \u2014Yvonne De Carlo\n |source = ''Yvonne: An Autobiography''{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}}\n |width  = 300px\n}}\n\nDe Carlo was born Margaret Yvonne Middleton on September 1, 1922, at [[St. Paul's Hospital (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Hospital]]{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada. Her nickname was \"Peggy\" because she was named after the silent film star [[Diana Serra Cary|Baby Peggy]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Her mother, Marie De Carlo (August 28, 1903 \u2013 December 19, 1993),<ref name='Marie Decarlo Middleton, \"California, Death Index, 1940-1997\"'>{{cite web|title=Marie Decarlo Middleton, \"California, Death Index, 1940-1997\"|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/VGPY-72X|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> was born in [[France]] to a [[Sicily|Sicilian]] father and a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother. Marie, a \"wayward and rebellious\" teenager, had aspired to become a dancer and worked as a milliner's apprentice until she met Peggy's father, William Shelto Middleton,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} a salesman from [[New Zealand]]<ref name=\"The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo\">{{cite news|last1=Bang|first1=Maureen|title=The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/45653015?searchTerm=yvonne%20de%20carlo%20new%20zealand&searchLimits=|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=The Australian Women's Weekly|date=November 15, 1972}}</ref> with \"piercing eyes of pale blue, and a wealth of straight black hair.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} Marie and William married in [[Alberta]], where they lived for a couple of months before returning to Vancouver.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} They moved in with Marie's parents, but the marriage was troubled.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=15}} Peggy had only two memories of her father: climbing up to his knee and crawling towards his feet.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=15}} By the time Peggy was three,{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=82}} William was involved in various swindles and fled Canada aboard a [[schooner]], promising to send for his wife and child.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=16}} Marie and Peggy never heard from him again; rumors said that he remarried twice and had more children, worked as an actor in silent films, or died aboard a ship.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Peggy later wrote, \"My own assumption is that he died before he had the chance to discover that his Baby Peggy had become a Hollywood actress, or I think he would have tried to contact me.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}}\n\nAfter William's departure, Marie left her parents' home and found work in a shop.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} Marie and Peggy lived in a succession of apartments in Vancouver, including one that had no furniture or stove,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=17}} and periodically returned to the De Carlo home, \"a huge white frame house\", at 1728 Comox Street in Vancouver's [[West End, Vancouver|West End]] neighborhood.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}} Marie's parents, Michele \"Papa\" De Carlo ({{circa}} 1873 \u2013 July 1, 1954)<ref name='Michael Decarlo, \"British Columbia Death Registrations, 1872-1986\"'>{{cite web|title=Michael Decarlo, \"British Columbia Death Registrations, 1872-1986\"|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-266-11671-106563-72?cc=1538285|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> and Margaret Purvis De Carlo (December 30, 1874 \u2013 October 26, 1949),<ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Decarlo - British Columbia Death Registrations|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FLRW-VLP|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> were religious, attended church regularly, and held services in the parlor.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=20}} Michele, a native of the city of [[Messina]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Michele De Carlo mentioned in the record of Kenneth Ross McKenzie and Constance Marguerite Anna Decarlo|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HY-DRGQ-DRB|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> had met Margaret in [[Nice]], France. They married in 1897, had four children, and settled in Canada.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=19}}\n\nDe Carlo attended Lord Roberts Elementary School,<ref name=\"History of Vancouver website\">{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/archives_yvonne.htm|website=History of Vancouver|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> located a block away from her grandparents' home.\n\nDe Carlo originally wanted to be a writer.<ref name=\"'Some day I'll meet Mr. Right'\">{{cite news|last1=Nash|first1=Roy|title=Some day I'll meet Mr. Right|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131240078|accessdate=18 March 2018|work=The News|date=November 28, 1953}}</ref> She was seven when a school assignment, a poem she wrote titled \"A Little Boy\", was entered in a contest run by ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}} She won and received a prize of five dollars, which according to De Carlo, meant as much to her at that time as if she had won the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=127}} She also wrote short plays, which she usually staged in her grandparents' house, and even adapted [[Charles Dickens]]' ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' for a neighborhood performance.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=127}}\n\nMarie wanted her daughter to have a career in show business and made sure Peggy received the necessary singing and dancing lessons. Peggy joined the choir of [[St. Paul's Anglican Church (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Anglican Church]] to strengthen her voice,<ref name=\"Films in Review, Volume 28\">{{cite book|title=Films in Review, Volume 28|date=1977|publisher=National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|page=217}}</ref> and when she was ten (or three, according to a 1982 interview{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=126}}), her mother enrolled her in the June Roper School of the Dance in Vancouver.<ref name=\"pryor\">\"The Unveiling of Yvonne (Salome) De Carlo: Herewith Some Early Film Entries in the Easter Week Sweepstakes\" by Thomas M. Pryor. ''New York Times'', March 25, 1945, p. X3.</ref> In May 1939, a ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' news item listed \"Yvonne de Carlo\" as one of the performers at the opening of Hy Singer's Palomar ballroom (also known as Palomar Supper Club) in Vancouver.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vancouver Dancery Opens As Night Club|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety134-1939-05#page/n39/mode/2up/search/yvonne+de+carlo|accessdate=18 March 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 3, 1939|page=41}}</ref>\n\n==Early Career==\n===Beginnings in Hollywood (1940\u20131942)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Maxie Rosenbloom in Harvard, Here I Come.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo in her first feature film, ''[[Harvard, Here I Come!]]'' (1941), starring boxer [[Maxie Rosenbloom]] (center)]]\nDe Carlo and her mother made several trips to [[Los Angeles]]. In 1940, she won second place in the Miss [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice]] beauty contest,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=4}} and placed fifth in that year's [[Miss California]] competition (and can be seen in that pageant at 0:36 of the British Path\u00e9 film \"A Matter of Figures\").<ref>\"Schoolgirl, 17 and Blond, Chosen as Miss California: Crowd of 100,000 Sees Parade of 50 Beauties as Venice Brings Four-Day Mardi Gras to Close\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' 12 August 1940: A1.</ref> At the Miss Venice contest, she was noticed by a booking agent who told her to audition for an opening in the chorus line at the [[Earl Carroll Theatre]] on Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=4}} De Carlo and her mother arrived at Earl Carroll's for the audition, but after learning that Carroll would have to examine her \"upper assets\" before hiring her,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=5}} De Carlo and her mother searched for work at another popular Hollywood nightclub, the Florentine Gardens.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=6}} They met N. T. G. -- [[Nils Granlund]], the proprietor of the Florentine Gardens\u2014who introduced De Carlo to the audience before she tap danced to \"[[Tea for Two (song)|Tea for Two]]\".{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=7}} Granlund then asked, \"Well, folks ... is she in or out?\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=8}} The audience responded with \"a rousing round of applause, with whistles and cheers,\" and De Carlo got the job.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoefling|first1=Larry J.|title=Nils Thor Granlund: Show Business Entrepreneur and America's First Radio Star|date=2008|publisher=Inlandia Press|location=Oklahoma|isbn=978-0-7864-4849-4|pages=178\u2013181|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VTfrVOw8c_0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> She started in the back of the chorus line, but after months of practice and hard work,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=10}} Granlund featured her in a \"[[King Kong]] number.\" In it, she danced, and cast off several chiffon veils before being carried away by a gorilla.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=11}} She was given more solo routines and also appeared in her first soundie.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=11}} She had been dancing at the Florentine Gardens only a few months when she was arrested by immigration officials and deported to Canada in late 1940.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=12}} In January 1941, Granlund sent a telegram to immigration officials pledging his sponsorship of De Carlo in the U.S., and affirmed his offer of steady employment, both requirements to reenter the country.<ref>Hoefling, p. 182.</ref>\n\nIn May 1941, she appeared in a revue, ''Hollywood Revels'', at the [[Orpheum Theatre (Los Angeles)|Orpheum Theatre]]. A critic from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reviewed it saying that the \"dancing of Yvonne de Carlo is especially notable.\"<ref>Kingsley, Grace. \"Bright Bill at Orpheum\", ''Los Angeles Times'', May 22, 1941, pg. 12.</ref> She made her radio debut with [[Edmund Lowe]] and [[Victor McLaglen]] who were performing extracts from a series based on their Flagg-Quint performances.<ref>De Carlo p 58</ref>\n\nDe Carlo wanted to act. At the encouragement of [[Artie Shaw]] who offered to pay her wage for a month,{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=59}} she quit the Florentine Gardens and hired a talent agent, Jack Pomeroy.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=60}} Pomeroy got De Carlo an uncredited role as a bathing beauty in a [[Columbia Pictures]] [[B film]], ''[[Harvard, Here I Come]]'' (1941). She had one line (\"Nowadays a girl must show a front\") in a scene with the film's star, [[Maxie Rosenbloom]]. Her salary was $25 and her work in the film got her into the [[Screen Actors Guild]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=60}} While at Columbia, she was featured (in a swimsuit) in ''The Kink of the Campus'', a short slapstick comedy with music, produced by the [[Three Stooges]] production team. Other roles were slow to follow, and De Carlo took a job in the chorus line of [[Earl Carroll]].\n\nWhile working for Carroll De Carlo got a one-line part in ''[[This Gun for Hire]]'' (1942) at Paramount. Carroll found out and fired her. De Carlo returned to N. T. G. at the Florentine Gardens.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=62}}\n\nIn December 1941, she was dancing in the revue ''Glamour Over Hollywood'' at Florentine Gardens.<ref>\"Travel: Taxco Basks in Grandeur and Beauty of Early Days\" ''Los Angeles Times'', December 28, 1941, pg. C4.</ref>{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=63}} America's entry into World War Two saw De Carlo and other Florentine dancers busy entertaining troops at USO shows.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=67}}<ref>\"Yvonne DeCarlo: Gilded Lily\". ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' (July 18, 2000).</ref>\n\nA skilled horsewoman, she appeared in a number of West Coast rodeos.<ref name=\"pryor\"/>\n\n===Paramount Pictures (1942\u20131944)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Deerslayer.jpg|thumb|De Carlo as Wah-Tah in ''[[Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]'' (1943)]]\nDe Carlo was cast as an island girl in ''[[Road to Morocco]]'' (1942) at Paramount. She was given a screen test for a role in ''[[The Moon and Sixpence (film)|The Moon and Sixpence]]'', but lost the part to Elena Verdugo. Paramount called her back for a small part in ''[[Lucky Jordan]]'' (also 1942) and she was cast in film for [[Republic Pictures|Republic]], ''[[Youth on Parade]]'' (again 1942), which she called a \"dreadful ... bomb\".<ref>De Carlo p. 70</ref>\n\nParamount then offered De Carlo a six-month contract, possibly going up to seven years, starting at $60 a week. She served as an extra in Paramount's ''[[The Crystal Ball (film)|The Crystal Ball]]'' (1943) of which she wrote \"only my left shoulder survived after editing\".<ref>De Carlo p 71</ref> Her scenes in ''[[Lucky Jordan]]'' (1942) were deleted but she had a small role in ''[[For Whom the Bell Tolls (film)|For Whom the Bell Tolls]]'' (1943). She could also be seen in ''[[Let's Face It (film)|Let's Face It]]'' (1943), ''[[So Proudly We Hail!]]'' (1943) and ''[[Salute for Three]]'' (1943), She was also kept busy in small roles and helping other actors shoot tests. \"I was the test queen at Paramount,\" she said later.<ref name=\"pryor\"/> But De Carlo was ambitious and wanted more. \"I'm not going to be just one of the girls,\" she said.<ref name=\"new\"/>\n\n[[Cecil B. DeMille]] saw De Carlo in ''So Proudly We Hail!'', and arranged for a screen-test and interview for the role of Tremartini in his film ''[[The Story of Dr. Wassell]]'' (1943), and subsequently chose her for a key role.<ref>\"Drama: 'Cousin' Rewrite Set; Hubbard Joining Cast\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', February 18, 1943, pg. A8.</ref><ref>\"Drama and Film: Gladys George Named Bankhead Successor Edward Small Plans Picture Glorifying Famous Maternity Center in Chicago\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', July 3, 1943, pg. 8.</ref> He ended up choosing [[Carol Thurston]] for the role and casting De Carlo in an uncredited part as a native girl, but promised to \"make it up\" to De Carlo on another film \"in the future.\"{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=110}}\n\nShe took two freelance assignments in 1943. When N. T. G. was signed by [[Monogram Pictures]] to film his revue for ''[[Rhythm Parade]]'', he recruited DeCarlo, who appears in the film as a Florentine Gardens dancer. She then took a leading role in ''[[The Deerslayer (1943 film)|Deerslayer]]''.\n\nShe returned to Paramount for an unbilled bit in ''[[True to Life (film)|True to Life]]'' (1943) and ''[[Standing Room Only (1944 film)|Standing Room Only]]'' (1944). De Carlo was billed in a short, ''Fun Time'' (1944) and went to [[MGM]] to play another \"native\" part (unbilled) in ''[[Kismet (1944 film)|Kismet]]'' (1944).\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' later dubbed De Carlo \"threat girl\" for [[Dorothy Lamour]] \"when Dotty wanted to break away from saronging.\"{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=110}}<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo, Technicolor Queen\">{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Sheilah|title=Yvonne DeCarlo, Technicolor Queen|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19490924&id=JC0sAAAAIBAJ&pg=4692,7182143|accessdate=April 28, 2014|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=September 24, 1949}}</ref> This had its origin when De Carlo was set to replace Dorothy Lamour in the lead of ''[[Rainbow Island (1944 film)|Rainbow Island]]'' (1944); however Lamour changed her mind about playing the role.<ref name=\"new\">\"Yvonne De Carlo Stands Out Again as 'Threat Girl': Carroll Cutie Has Spotlight in Sarong Set Yvonne De Carlo Causes Concern in Sarong Circles\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', June 3, 1945, pg. B1.</ref> De Carlo was given a bit part in the final movie.\n\nDe Carlo played further unbilled roles in ''[[Here Come the Waves]]'' (1944), ''[[Practically Yours]]'' (1944), and ''[[Bring On the Girls (film)|Bring on the Girls]]'' (1945). Paramount then decided not to renew her contract option<ref>De Carlo p 84</ref> but renewed Lamour's contract.\n\n==Stardom==\n===''Salome, Where She Danced'' (1944\u20131945)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Salome, Where She Danced.jpg|thumbnail|De Carlo as Anna Maria, an Austrian dancer, in ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945)]]\nDe Carlo was screen tested by [[Universal Pictures|Universal]], who were looking for an exotic glamour girl in the mold of [[Maria Montez]] and [[Acquanetta]].<ref>De Carlo p. 84</ref> The test was seen by [[Walter Wanger]] who was making an adventure film in Technicolor, ''[[Salome, Where She Danced]]'' (1945). Wanger later claimed he discovered De Carlo when looking at footage for another actor in which De Carlo also happened to appear ([[Milburn Stone]]).<ref>\"Hollywood Memoranda: Noted in Hollywood\", ''New York Times'', September 24, 1944, pg. X1.</ref>\n\nWanger tested De Carlo several times and Universal signed her to a long term contract at $150 a week. In September 1944, it was announced De Carlo was cast in the lead of ''Salome'' over a reported 20,000 other young women.<ref name=\"Yvonne De Carlo Chosen for Role Over '20,000 Beautiful Girls'\"/><ref>Schallert, Edwin. \"Guild Player Deemed Fit Valentino Double: David Bruce Wins Acting Opportunity in Wanger's Film Drama, ''Salome''\" ''Los Angeles Times'', September 19, 1944, pg. A8.</ref>\n\nAnother source says 21 Royal Canadian Air Force bombardier students who loved her as a pinup star campaigned to get her the role.<ref>\"From Pinup to Star!\", ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', November 12, 1944, p. D5.</ref> De Carlo later said this was done at her behest; she took several pictures of herself in a revealing costume and persuaded two childhood friends from Vancouver, Reginald Reid and Kenneth Ross McKenzie, who had become pilots, to arrange their friends to lobby on her behalf,<ref name=\"pryor\"/> writing in her memoirs that the whole thing was Wanger's idea.<ref>De Carlo p. 89</ref>\n\nThough not a critical success, ''Salome'' was a box office favorite, and the heavily promoted De Carlo was hailed as an up-and-coming star. In his review for the film, [[Bosley Crowther]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote:\n\n<blockquote>Miss De Carlo has an agreeable contralto singing voice, all the 'looks' one girl could ask for, and, moreover, she dances with a sensuousness which must have caused the [[Motion Picture Production Code|Hays office]] some anguish. The script, however, does not give her much chance to prove her acting talents.<ref name=\"Salome Where She Danced (1945) The Screen; 'Rose's Diamond Horseshoe,' With Betty Grable, at Roxy-- 'Salome, Where She Danced,' Is Newcomer of the Criterion At Loew's\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Salome Where She Danced (1945) The Screen; 'Rose's Diamond Horseshoe,' With Betty Grable, at Roxy-- 'Salome, Where She Danced,' Is Newcomer of the Criterion At Loew's|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9c07e3df143bee3bbc4b53dfb366838e659ede|accessdate=April 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 3, 1945}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Universal-International (1945\u20131950)===\n[[File:Yvonne in Song of Scheherezade.jpg|thumb|De Carlo in the trailer for ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947)]]\n''Salome, Where She Danced'' was released by Universal who signed de Carlo to a long-term contract. She was used by the studio as a backup star to [[Maria Montez]], and her second movie for the studio saw her step into a role rejected by Montez: the Western ''[[Frontier Gal]]'' (1946) alongside Rod Cameron.<ref name=\"new\"/> In 1946, exhibitors voted De Carlo the ninth-most promising \"star of tomorrow.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17994035|title=The Stars of To-morrow|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=September 10, 1946|accessdate=April 24, 2012|page=11|publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Like ''Salome'', it was shot in Technicolor.\n\nDe Carlo followed ''Frontier Gal'' with a top-billed role in [[Walter Reisch]]'s Technicolor musical ''[[Song of Scheherazade]]'' (1947), co-starring [[Brian Donlevy]] and [[Jean-Pierre Aumont]]. [[Tilly Losch]], an Austrian dancer and friend of Reisch, coached De Carlo in her three dancing solos.<ref>De Carlo p. 114</ref> The film was a hit, making over $2 million.\n\nDe Carlo wanted to act in different types of movies. She applied to play the part of a waitress in ''[[A Double Life (1947 film)|A Double Life]]'' (1947) but lost out to [[Shelley Winters]].<ref>De Carlo p 122</ref> Instead, Universal put her back in Technicolor for ''[[Slave Girl (film)|Slave Girl]]'' (1947), made with the producers of ''Frontier Gal''. It was another solid commercial success. De Carlo was given a small role in ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947), a prison movie starring [[Burt Lancaster]] and produced by [[Mark Hellinger]]. It was her first movie in black and white since becoming a star and her first to get good reviews.\n\nShe played [[Lola Montez]] in ''[[Black Bart (film)|Black Bart]]'' (1948), a Technicolor Western with [[Dan Duryea]] for director [[George Sherman]]. Duryea and Sherman worked with her again on ''[[River Lady (film)|River Lady]]'' (1948). De Carlo called these films \"physically taxing but not creatively inspiring.\"<ref>De Carlo p 127</ref> The ''New York Times'' later summarised them as \"a series of routine costume adventures as a tough but good-natured minx from across the tracks who wades into society and inevitably backtracks with a bloke of her own caliber.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/06/21/archives/yvonne-de-carlo-in-technicolor-feature.html|newspaper=New York Times|title=Yvonne de Carlo in Technicolor Feature|last=H. H. T.|date=June 21, 1952}}</ref>\n\nShe romanced Tony Martin in ''[[Casbah (film)|Casbah]]'' (1948), a musical remake of ''[[Algiers (film)|Algiers]]'' (1938) made for Martin's own production company but released through Universal. De Carlo was reluctant to be in it because, though she would receive top billing over Martin, she did not get the female lead. That part went to Swedish newcomer [[M\u00e4rta Tor\u00e9n]]. However, studio head [[William Goetz]] insisted<ref>De Carlo p 129</ref> that De Carlo play Inez, the role [[Sigrid Gurie]] acted in the 1938 version. She also sang the film's song ''For Every Man There's a Woman'', which was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. The film flopped at the box office, de Carlo's first flop since becoming a star.\n\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo in Criss Cross.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo in the trailer for ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949)]]\nDe Carlo then received an offer from Mark Hellinger to make another film with Burt Lancaster: the [[film noir]] ''[[Criss Cross (film)|Criss Cross]]'' (1949). This time De Carlo had a larger role, as a femme fatale, Anna. [[Bosley Crowther]] noted that De Carlo was \"trying something different as Anna. The change is welcome, even though Miss de Carlo's performance is uneven. In that respect, she is right in step with most everything else about ''Criss Cross.''\"<ref name=\"Criss Cross (1948) Burt Lancaster Same Old Tough Guy\">{{cite news|title=Movie Review: Criss Cross (1948) Burt Lancaster Same Old Tough Guy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9403E5D7103EE03BBC4A52DFB5668382659EDE|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 12, 1949}}</ref> The film has become regarded as a classic and De Carlo considered the role the highlight of her career to date.<ref>Strong, E J., \"Yvonne De Carlo May Brave Suspension, So She Can Return to Troops: GI's Show Needs Told by Actress\", ''Los Angeles Times'', October 3, 1948, pg. D1.</ref> [[Tony Curtis]] made his debut in the movie, in a scene dancing with De Carlo.\n\nDe Carlo was keen to make more movies along this line but Universal put her back in Technicolor Westerns with ''[[Calamity Jane and Sam Bass]]'' (1949), playing [[Calamity Jane]], directed by Sherman, alongside [[Howard Duff]].\n\nShe played a role intended for [[Deanna Durbin]] in ''[[The Gal Who Took the West]]'' (1950), for director [[Fred de Cordova]]. The movie gave her a chance to show off her singing voice. Trained in opera and a former child chorister at St Paul's Anglican Church, Vancouver, De Carlo possessed a large [[vocal range]].<ref name='\"The Independent\" obituary'>{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo [Obituary]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/yvonne-de-carlo-431761.html|accessdate=January 11, 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|quote=Impressed with her large vocal range ...}}</ref> She was meant to be in ''[[Bagdad (film)|Bagdad]]'' (1949) but suffered a miscarriage and was ill, so the studio cast [[Maureen O'Hara]].<ref>de Carlo p 145</ref>\n\nDe Cordova directed de Carlo in ''[[Buccaneer's Girl]]'' (1950), a pirate movie set in 1810s New Orleans opposite [[Philip Friend]]. The director later called De Carlo \"a doll ... underrated as an actress. She was most professional, worked hard, was very good at her craft, possibly was not a first class star but came in on schedule. She knew her lines, she danced and sang rather well, and she wanted very much to be a bigger star than she ever became.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/justmakingmovies00davi#page/132/mode/1up|title=Just Making Movies: Company Directors on the Studio System|page=132|first=Roland L.|last=Davis|publisher=University of Press Mississippi|year=2005}}</ref>\n\nShe toured US army bases singing, then was in ''[[The Desert Hawk (1950 film)|The Desert Hawk]]'' (1950), an \"Eastern\" with [[Richard Greene]]. She made a Western with Sherman, ''[[Tomahawk (film)|Tomahawk]]'' (1951), opposite [[Van Heflin]], which was popular.\n\nDe Carlo toured extensively to promote her films and entertained US troops in Europe. She also began singing on television.<ref>Yvonne De Carlo Pins Hopes for Future on Switch to Dramatic and Singing Roles SCHUER, PHILIP K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]27 May 1951: D1.</ref>\n\nShe received an offer from England to make a comedy, ''[[Hotel Sahara]]'' (1951) with [[Peter Ustinov]]. While in England, she asked Universal to release her from her contract, though it still had three months to go, and the studio agreed.<ref>Brady, Thomas F. \"Paramount Buys Two New Stories: Giler Melodrama and Clark Adventure Acquired by Studio --Jean Arthur Gets Role\", ''New York Times'', January 30, 1951, pg. 21.</ref>\n\n===Post-Universal (1951\u20131954)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and John Ireland in Hurricane Smith.jpg|thumb|De Carlo and fellow Vancouverite [[John Ireland (actor)|John Ireland]] in ''[[Hurricane Smith (1952 film)|Hurricane Smith]]'' (1952), a Paramount Pictures release]]\nWhile in England, De Carlo recorded two singles, \"Say Goodbye\" and \"I Love a Man\".<ref>Studio Wants Larry Olivier to Co-Star with Ava Gardner: Looking at Hollywood.....\nHopper, Hedda. Chicago Daily Tribune 20 Apr 1951: b2.</ref> In March 1951 she signed a new contract with Universal to make one film a year for three years<ref>Hopper, Hedda. \"New Contract to Let Yvonne Travel: Looking at Hollywood\", ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', March 7, 1951, pg. A-14.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo went to Paramount to make a Western, ''[[Silver City (1951 film)|Silver City]]'' (1951) for producer Nat Holt, co-starring alongside [[Edmond O'Brien]] for a fee of $50,000.<ref>De Carlo p 156</ref>\n\nIn 1951,<ref>\"Yvonne De Carlo Pins Hopes for Future on Switch to Dramatic and Singing Roles\" Schuer, Philip K. ''Los Angeles Times'' 27 May 1951: D1.</ref><ref name=\"Slave Girl Wants Freedom\" /><ref name=\"Yvonne de Carlo Gets Hollywood Opera Role\">{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|authorlink1=Hedda Hopper|title=Yvonne de Carlo Gets Hollywood Opera Role|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1951/06/02/page/16/article/yvonne-de-carlo-gets-hollywood-opera-role/|accessdate=December 27, 2016|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 2, 1951}}</ref> De Carlo accepted an offer to open the thirtieth season of the [[Hollywood Bowl]] singing the [[breeches role]] of Prince Orlovsky in five performances of the opera ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' (''The Bat''), from July 10 to July 14.<ref>{{cite journal|title=63 to 86 Men For Hwd. Bowl Symph Series|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 14, 1951|page=12|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=157}} The performances were conducted by noted film composer [[Franz Waxman]]. In her autobiography she described her participation in ''Die Fledermaus'' as \"a rewarding experience, the aesthetic highlight of my life.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=157}}\n\nIn August 1951, De Carlo became the first American film star to visit the [[Israel|State of Israel]], giving concerts in [[Haifa]], [[Ramat Gan]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Jaffa]] which were exploited for propaganda purposes.<ref>\"Yvonne De Carlo Admits Serious Loves, but Chooses to Keep Them Mysterious\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'', June 22, 1952, p. D1.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Harrison|first1=Scott|title=Actress Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://framework.latimes.com/2011/11/23/actress-yvonne-de-carlo|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> She drew capacity audiences and was \"royally received\" by the Israeli government and the public.<ref name=\"Jerusalem likes De Carlo\">{{cite news|title=Jerusalem likes De Carlo|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 19, 1951}}</ref> Her performances consisted of singing and dancing routines from her films.<ref name=\"Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East\">{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob|authorlink1=Bob Thomas (reporter)|title=Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/19627183|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=[[Moberly Monitor-Index]]|date=September 27, 1951}}</ref> Furthermore, she found that her films were extremely popular there, saying, \"Every time I played a concert, someone would yell, 'Sing something from ''[[Casbah (film)|Casbah]]''.'\"<ref name=\"Sultry Yvonne Now Respects Exotic Roles; Natives Love Those Films, Miss DeCarlo Finds in Near East\"/> About the warm reception she received in Israel, she told columnist [[Louella Parsons]]:\n\n{{quote|Everyone in Israel was so wonderful to me, and I'll never forget the speech the Mayor of Jerusalem, Rabbi S. Z. Shragar, made. It had to be translated because he spoke in Hebrew. He is an orthodox Jew and lives up to his religion. He received me in his office and served me Turkish coffee, and I was told no woman had ever been invited to have coffee in his office before. He welcomed me to Israel in a gracious, kindly manner that I shall never forget. He gave me what they call a special blessing, not only for myself, but for all artists who were to come later.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parsons|first1=Louella|title=Tells Of Israel: Yvonne De Carlo Impressed By Reception In New Nation|work=Cumberland Sunday Times|date=November 25, 1951}}</ref>}}\n\nDe Carlo returned early from Tel Aviv to make ''[[The San Francisco Story]]'' (1952) with [[Joel McCrea]]. It was the first of a two-picture deal with Fidelity Pictures; the second was to be ''The Scarlet Flame'' about Brazil's battle for independence, which was never made.<ref>By THOMAS M PRYOR Special to The New York Times. (1951, Oct 13). FIDELITY TO FILM 'SCARLET FLAME'. New York Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/112132457</ref>\n\nShe made her live TV debut in \"Another Country\" for ''[[Lights Out (radio show)|Lights Out]]'' (1952). De Carlo wanted to make a film for [[Sydney Box]] called ''Queen of Sheba'' with [[Peter Ustinov]] as Solomon but it was never made.<ref>Drama: Yvonne De Carlo Named for British 'Sheba;' Find From 'Guys and Dolls' Set Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 21 Sep 1951: B9.</ref>\n\nShe went back to Universal for the first movie under her new contract, ''[[Scarlet Angel]]'' (1952) with [[Rock Hudson]].\n\nAt Paramount she did another film for Nat Holt, ''[[Hurricane Smith (1952 film)|Hurricane Smith]]'' (1952), then she appeared in \"Madame 44\" for ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'' (1952). She announced plans to form her own production company with her agent, Vancouver Productions.<ref>Looking at Hollywood: Yvonne De Carlo and Agent Form Own Movie Company Hopper, Hedda. ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' 5 Aug 1952: a2.</ref>  However, as she later wrote \"absolutely nothing\" came of this.<ref>De Carlo p 167</ref>\n\nDe Carlo went to MGM to make ''[[Sombrero (film)|Sombrero]]'' (1953), mostly shot in Mexico. She liked her character because it was \"almost madonnalike.It is a role that demands the most sincerity for its proper interpretation. Many pictures that I have done perhaps offered me typical outdoor parts or western, heroine parts. So long as I could convey a flashy sort of impression it was alright... I don't deny the importance of such parts for me. They are excellent. But is stands to reason that as one goes on one seeks less superficial assignments.<ref name=\"myst\">Yvonne De Carlo Admits Serious Loves, but Chooses to Keep Them Mysterious\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 22 June 1952: D1.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo was reunited with Hudson for ''[[Sea Devils (1953 film)|Sea Devils]]'' (1953), a Napoleonic adventure tale shot in Britain and France released through [[RKO]]. This meant she had to postpone a film she was going to make for [[Edward Small]], ''Savage Frontier''. She was offered a role in ''[[Innocents in Paris]]'' (1953) but ultimately did not appear in the film.<ref name=\"myst\"/>\n\nBack in the US she an adventure film set in the desert, ''[[Fort Algiers]]'' (1953),  for [[United Artists]], starring [[Carlos Thompson]], whom de Carlo had recommended.\n\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Alec Guinness in The Captain's Paradise.jpg|thumb|De Carlo with [[Alec Guinness]] in ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953)]]\nShe made her third film in Britain with the comedy ''[[The Captain's Paradise]]'' (1953), as one of two wives a ship captain (played by [[Alec Guinness]]) keeps in separate ports. De Carlo played Nita, the sensual wife who lives in Morocco, while [[Celia Johnson]] played Maud, the demure wife who lives in Gibraltar. The film was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Story]], and ''The New York Times'' critic Bosley Crowther commended her performance by writing, \"And Miss De Carlo, as the siren, 'the mate of the tiger' in Mr. G. [Guinness], is wonderfully candid and suggestive of the hausfrau in every dame.\"<ref name=\"Captain's Paradise (1953) The Screen: New British Comedy Arrives; Alec Guinness Keeps Two Wives Happy in 'The Captain's Paradise' at Paris But Yvonne De Carlo and Celia Johnson Finally Cause the Downfall of Skipper\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Captain's Paradise (1953) The Screen: New British Comedy Arrives; Alec Guinness Keeps Two Wives Happy in 'The Captain's Paradise' at Paris But Yvonne De Carlo and Celia Johnson Finally Cause the Downfall of Skipper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F00EED71331E53BBC4151DFBF668388649EDE|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 29, 1953}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo made a fourth film in England, ''[[Happy Ever After (1954 film)|Happy Ever After]]'' (1954) with [[David Niven]], then was called back to the US do to a contemporary comedy on TV, ''[[The Backbone of America]]'' (1953) with [[Wendell Corey]]. In 1954, after the success of ''The Captain's Paradise,'' she expressed a desire to do more comedy:\n\n<blockquote>I've had my share of sirens and am happy to get away from them, no matter what the part. Just to look pretty on the screen as a romantic lead is probably all right, but \u2013 so what? I'd much rather do something in a good Western provided there's plenty of action. Action is what I like.<ref name=\"edwin\">\"Yvonne's Persistence Making Believers of Her Critics\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 2 May 1954: E1.</ref></blockquote>\n\nDe Carlo went back to Universal to make a Western with McCrea, ''[[Border River]]'' (1954), directed by Sherman. She went to Italy for ''[[The Contessa's Secret]]'' (1954) and returned to Hollywood for the independently produced ''[[Passion (1954 film)|Passion]]'' (1954). She wrote a 42-page treatment for a science-fiction film ''Operation Sram'', which was not made.<ref>Schallert, E. (1954, Jun 21). De mille gets vincent price as cruel builder; 'nightshade' on schedule. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/166630481</ref> De Carlo made the Western ''[[Shotgun (1955 film)|Shotgun]]'' (1955) with [[Sterling Hayden]] for Allied Artists. She did \"Hot Cargo\" for ''[[Screen Director's Playhouse]]'' (1956) with [[Rory Calhoun]] directed by [[Tay Garnett]].<ref>De Carlo Cover\nThe Washington Post and Times Herald (1954-1959); Washington, D.C. [Washington, D.C]01 Jan 1956: J1.</ref>\n\nDe Carlo made her third film for Universal under her new contract in ''[[Raw Edge (film)|Raw Edge]]'' (1956).  Republic starred her as [[Minna Planer|Minna Wagner]] in a biopic of [[Richard Wagner]], ''[[Magic Fire]]'' (1956). On TV she was in \"The Sainted General\" for ''[[Star Stage]]'' (1956). [[Republic Pictures|Republic]] reunited her with Duff in ''[[Flame of the Islands]]'' (1956), shot in the Bahamas.\n\n===''The Ten Commandments'' and last notable film roles (1954\u20131963)===\n[[File:Screenshot of Yvonne De Carlo in The Ten Commandments.jpg|thumb|left|De Carlo as Sephora in ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)]]\nIn September 1954,<ref>{{cite news|title=Yvonne De Carlo yesterday was cast by Cecil B. DeMille in the role of Sephora, Jethro's daughter and the shepherd girl who married Moses, in ''The Ten Commandments''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 15, 1954}}</ref> producer-director Cecil B. DeMille cast her as [[Zipporah]], the wife of Moses (played by [[Charlton Heston]]), in his biblical epic ''The Ten Commandments'', a [[Paramount Pictures]] production that premiered in November 1956. In his autobiography, DeMille explained he decided to cast De Carlo as Moses' wife after his casting director, Bert McKay, called his attention to one scene she played in ''Sombrero''. Even though the film \"was a picture far removed in theme from ''The Ten Commandments'',\" wrote DeMille, \"I sensed in her a depth, an emotional power, a womanly strength which the part of Sephora needed and which she gave it.\"<ref name=\"The autobiography of Cecil B. DeMille\">{{cite book|last=DeMille|first=Cecil Blount|title=The Autobiography of Cecil B. DeMille|year=1959|publisher=Prentice-Hall|page=416}}</ref>\n\nShe prepared extensively for the role, taking weaving lessons at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], and shepherding lessons in the [[San Fernando Valley]].{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}} Months before filming began, she had worked on the part with a drama coach.<ref name=\"Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne\">{{cite news|title=Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19580718&id=T3svAAAAIBAJ&pg=6984,3681522|accessdate=October 16, 2014|work=[[Deseret News|The Deseret News]]|date=July 18, 1958}}</ref> Her scenes were shot on Paramount's sound stages in 1955. Her performance received praise from critics. Crowther, the ''New York Times'' critic, was impressed: \"Yvonne DeCarlo as the Midianite shepherdess to whom Moses is wed is notably good in a severe role.\"<ref name=\"Movie Review: The Ten Commandments\">{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|title=Movie Review: The Ten Commandments|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF1730A22CAA484CC1B7799A8E6896|accessdate=April 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 9, 1956}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that she \"is very fine as the simple Sephora,\"<ref>{{cite web|title='The Ten Commandments': Read THR's 1956 Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ten-commandments-1956-movie-review-754677|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[New York Daily News]]'' noticed that she \"plays the wife of Moses with conviction.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Flashback: Original 1956 review of 'The Ten Commandments' in the Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/flashback-stars-ten-commandment-article-1.2040699|website=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe fell in love with stuntman Bob Morgan while visiting the filming of ''The Ten Commandments'' in Egypt in 1954.{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} They married in 1955, and their first son, Bruce, was born in 1956. DeMille became Bruce's godfather.{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}} Her second pregnancy meant she had to turn down the role of the female pirate DeMille had given her in his next production, ''[[The Buccaneer (1958 film)|The Buccaneer]]'' (1958).{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}}\n\nIt was announced she would team with [[Vittorio De Sica]] in an adaptation of ''[[The Baker's Wife]]'' to be shot in English and Italian<ref>Hopper, H. (1955, Jun 11). De carlo, de sica to do 'baker's wife'. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/166766450</ref> but the film was never made. Neither were two projects de Carlo was meant to make in Italy following ''Raw Edge'', ''The Mistress of Lebanon Castle'' with [[Trevor Howard]] and ''Honeymoon in Italy''.<ref>Drama: 'Something of Value' Bid DNow Centers on Travers; John Williams Resuming\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 22 Oct 1955: 13.</ref>\n\nInstead De Carlo co-starred with [[George Sanders]] and [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]] in ''[[Death of a Scoundrel]]'' (1956). ''The New York Times'' commended her performance as Bridget Kelly: \"Yvonne De Carlo does a solid and professional job as the adoring petty thief who rises to eminence with him [Sanders' character].\"<ref>{{cite web|title='Death of a Scoundrel' at Loew's State|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C06E7DB1230E23BBC4E53DFB767838D649EDE|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> On the small screen she was in \"Skits & Sketches\" for ''[[Shower of Stars]]'' (1957). She was also in ''[[Schlitz Playhouse]]'' (1957)\n\nDe Carlo released an [[LP record]] of standards called ''[[Yvonne De Carlo Sings]]'' on Masterseal Records, a subsidiary label of [[Remington Records]], in 1957. Orchestrated by future film composer [[John Williams]] under the pseudonym \"John Towner,\" the album contains ten tracks, \"End of a Love Affair\", \"[[In the Blue of Evening]]\", \"[[I Got It Bad (and That Ain't Good)]]\", \"[[Am I Blue?]]\", \"[[Little Girl Blue (song)|Little Girl Blue]]\", \"[[Blue Moon (1934 song)|Blue Moon]]\", \"[[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\", \"[[My Blue Heaven (song)|My Blue Heaven]]\", \"[[Mood Indigo]]\", \"[[One for My Baby (and One More for the Road)]]\".\n[[File:Yvonne de carlo - 1957.jpg|thumb|With [[Clark Gable]] in ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957)]]\nAs a result of the great success and positive reviews of ''The Ten Commandments'', De Carlo was offered lead roles in two [[Warner Bros.]] films that would be shot at the same time: ''[[The Helen Morgan Story]]'' and ''[[Band of Angels]]'', based on [[Robert Penn Warren]]'s novel. De Carlo chose the latter because her co-star would be [[Clark Gable]], one of her favorite actors.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=199}} The title refers to the short life expectancy of the black soldiers who fought with the Union troops in the Civil War, but the story is mainly about Amantha \"Manty\" Starr, a mixed-race [[Southern belle]] who is sold as a slave after her father's death and discovers that her deceased mother was a black slave on her father's plantation. Amantha is then taken to [[New Orleans]] where she is bought by plantation owner Hamish Bond (Gable), who falls in love with her. The film was both a critical and financial disappointment at the time of release.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=200}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Band of Angels (1957) - Notes|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/16194/Band-of-Angels/notes.html|website=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo was in \"Verdict of Three\" for ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' (1958). She made a [[French Foreign Legion]] movie with [[Victor Mature]], ''[[Timbuktu (1959 film)|Timbuktu]],'' directed by [[Jacques Tourneur]] (1958). She unsuccessfully auditioned for the Broadway musical ''[[Destry Rides Again (musical)|Destry Rides Again]]'' losing out to [[Dolores Gray]].<ref>De Carlo p 202</ref>\n\nIn May 1958,<ref name=\"De Carlo Signed for Italian 'Magdalene'\">{{cite news|title=De Carlo Signed for Italian 'Magdalene'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 20, 1958}}</ref> De Carlo was signed to play [[Mary Magdalene]] in the Italian biblical epic ''[[The Sword and the Cross]]'' (tentatively titled ''The Great Sinner'' and released in the United States as ''Mary Magdalene''), with [[Jorge Mistral]] as her love interest, the Roman Gaius Marcellus, and [[Rossana Podest\u00e0]] as her sister, Martha. The film's director, [[Carlo Ludovico Bragaglia]], later remembered that \"producer, Ottavio Poggi, had sent the provisional script to America, so Yvonne De Carlo could read it and decide on her participation in the film. She read it and got very excited, agreeing to play the role of Magdalene.\"<ref name=\"Nato col cinema\">{{cite book|last1=Antonelli|first1=Lamberto|last2=Laura|first2=Ernesto G.|title=Nato col cinema: Carlo Ludovico Braggalia: cent'anni tra arti e cinema|date=1992|publisher=A.N.C.C.I.|page=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rmxZAAAAMAAJ&dq=Lei+lo+lesse+e+se+ne+entusiasm%C3%B2+moltissimo%2C+accettando+di+interpretare+il+ruolo&q=Yvonne+De+Carlo|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The film was shot in English and later dubbed in Italian.<ref name=\"Hard Work Pays Off For Yvonne\" />\n\nDe Carlo put together a nightclub act and toured with it in South America. She guest starred on ''[[Bonanza]]'' (\"A Rose for Lotta\", 1959), ''[[Adventures in Paradise (TV series)|Adventures in Paradise]]'' (\"Isle of Eden\", 1960), ''[[Death Valley Days]]'' (\"The Lady Was an M.D\", 1961), ''[[Follow the Sun (TV series)|Follow the Sun]]'' (\"The Longest Crap Game in History\" [1961] and \"Annie Beeler's Place\", 1962) and ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]'' (\"Who Killed Beau Sparrow?\", 1963). She also played ''Destry Rides Again'' in summer stock.\n[[File:John Wayne-Yvonne De Carlo in McLintock!.jpg|thumb|left|With [[John Wayne]] in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963)]]\nDe Carlo's husband had been permanently crippled while working as a stunt man on ''[[How the West Was Won (film)|How the West Was Won]]'' (1963), eventually losing his leg. De Carlo took any job going, appearing in night club acts across the country as well as a play in stock, ''Third Best Sport''.\n\nTo help out, [[John Wayne]] offered her the supporting role of Louise Warren, the title character's cook in ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963), with Wayne and [[Maureen O'Hara]]. She was second billed in a Western ''[[Law of the Lawless]]'' (1964) and played the Spanish dancer Dolores in the [[Bob Hope]] comedy ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964).\n\nDe Carlo was in \"The Night the Monkey Died\" for ''[[The Greatest Show on Earth (TV series)|The Greatest Show on Earth]]'' (1964). She took over a role on ''[[Enter Laughing]]'' on Broadway for a week, and played in it when the production went on tour.\n\n==Later Career==\n===''The Munsters'' (1964\u20131966)===\n[[File:Lily.Munster.jpg|thumb|right|Publicity photo of De Carlo as [[Lily Munster]]]]\nShe was in debt by 1964 when she signed a contract with [[Universal Studios]] to perform the female lead role in ''[[The Munsters]]'' opposite [[Fred Gwynne]]. She was also the producers' choice to play [[Lily Munster]] when [[Joan Marshall]], who played the character (originally called \"Phoebe\"), was dropped from consideration for the role. When De Carlo was asked how a glamorous actress could succeed as a ghoulish matriarch of a haunted house, she replied simply, \"I follow the directions I received on the first day of shooting: 'Play her just like ''[[The Donna Reed Show|Donna Reed]]''.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5fcgAAAAIBAJ&pg=1176,787858&dq=john+astin&hl=en|title=The Day \u2013 Google News Archive|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> She sang and played the [[harp]] in at least one episode (\"Far Out Munsters\") of ''The Munsters''.\n\nAfter the show's cancellation, she reprised her role as Lily Munster in the [[Technicolor]] film ''[[Munster, Go Home!]]'' (1966), partially in hopes of renewing interest in the sitcom. Despite the attempt, ''The Munsters'' was cancelled after 70 episodes. Of the sitcom and its cast and crew, she said: \"It was a happy show with audience appeal for both children and adults. It was a happy show behind the scenes, too; we all enjoy working with each other.\"<ref name=\"Monstrous Mayor\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Erskine|title=Monstrous Mayor|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19660424&id=JGocAAAAIBAJ&pg=5514,4038787|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=April 24, 1966}}</ref> Years later, in 1987, she said: \"I think Yvonne De Carlo was more famous than Lily, but I gained the younger audience through ''The Munsters''. And it was a steady job.\"<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo Enjoys 'Munsters' Rebirth\">{{cite news|last1=Oricchio|first1=Michael|title=Yvonne DeCarlo Enjoys 'Munsters' Rebirth|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19870530&id=bMFPAAAAIBAJ&pg=5401,8081705|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=[[Star-Banner|Ocala Star-Banner]]|date=May 30, 1987}}</ref>\n\n===Stage work and ''Follies'' (1967\u20131973)===\nAfter ''The Munsters'', she guest starred in \"The Moulin Ruse Affair\" in ''[[The Girl from UNCLE]]'' (1967) and \"The Raiders\" for ''[[Custer]]'' (1967) and episodes of ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''.\n\nShe starred in ''[[Hostile Guns]]'' (1967) and ''[[Arizona Bushwhackers]]'' (1968), a pair of low-budget westerns produced by [[A. C. Lyles]] and released by Paramount Pictures. During this time, she also had a supporting role in the 1968 thriller ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]''.\n\nAfter 1967, De Carlo became increasingly active in musicals, appearing in off-Broadway productions of ''[[Pal Joey (musical)|Pal Joey]]'' and ''Catch Me If You Can''. In early 1968 she joined [[Donald O'Connor]] in a 15-week run of ''[[Little Me (musical)|Little Me]]'' staged between Lake Tahoe and Las Vegas and she did a five-month tour in ''[[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|Hello Dolly]]''. Later she toured in ''[[Cactus Flower (play)|Cactus Flower]]''.<ref name=\"De Carlo 1987\">{{cite book|last=De Carlo|first=Yvonne|author2=Warren, Doug|title=Yvonne: An Autobiography|year=1987|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9780312002176|url=https://archive.org/details/yvonneautobiogra00deca_0}}</ref>\n\nDe Carlo continued to appear in films such as ''[[The Delta Factor (film)|The Delta Factor]]'' (1970) and had a notable part in [[Russ Meyer]]'s ''[[The Seven Minutes (film)|The Seven Minutes]]'' (1971). The ''Los Angeles Times'' said about the latter that De Carlo featured in \"an improbable sequence pulled off with verve by the still glamorous star.\"<ref>Thomas, K. (1971, Sep 08). 'Seven' attacks censorship. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/156863129</ref>\n\nHer defining stage role was as \"Carlotta Campion\" in [[Harold Prince]]'s production of the [[Stephen Sondheim]] musical ''[[Follies]]'' in 1971-72.<ref name = \"De Carlo 1987\"/> Playing a washed-up star at a reunion of old theater colleagues, she introduced the song \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\".{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=140}} De Carlo says she was told the part was written especially for her.<ref>De Carlo p 216</ref>\n\nIn October 1972, De Carlo arrived in [[Australia]] to replace [[Cyd Charisse]] in [[Edgley International|Michael Edgley]]'s production of ''[[No, No, Nanette]]''.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=226}} Her opening night was on November 6, 1972 at [[Her Majesty's Theatre, Melbourne|Her Majesty's Theatre]] in [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"The first Aussie Yvonne met was a kangaroo\" /> The show moved on to [[Adelaide]],{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=229}} [[Sydney]], and then to several [[New Zealand]] cities.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=231}} It closed in the fall of 1973, and De Carlo returned to the United States.\n\nIn late 1973 and early 1974, she starred in a production of [[Ben Bagley]]'s ''Decline and Fall of the Entire World as Seen Through the Eyes of Cole Porter'' in San Diego.\n\nIn May 1975, she starred in the San Bernardino Civic Light Opera's production of ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]'' at the [[California Theatre (San Bernardino)|California Theatre of the Performing Arts]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=233}} ''[[The San Bernardino Sun]]'' described her performance as \"brilliant\" and wrote, \"a packed house watched Yvonne De Carlo give a new dimension to Margo Channing, a part she was playing for the first time, but nonetheless, a part she was very well suited for.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Jimmy|title=Yvonne DeCarlo brilliant in 'Applause'|work=The Sun-Telegram|date=May 11, 1975|page=D-6}}</ref>\n\n===Later career (1974\u20131995)===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo (1979).jpg|thumb|200px|right|De Carlo at the National Film Society convention, May 1979]]\nDe Carlo appeared in ''[[The Girl on the Late, Late Show]]'' (1974), ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1974 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1974), ''[[Arizona Slim]]'' (1974), ''[[The Intruder (1975 film)|The Intruder]]'' (1975), ''[[Blazing Stewardesses]]'' (1975), ''[[It Seemed Like a Good Idea at the Time]]'' (1975), ''[[Black Fire (film)|Black Fire]]'' (1975), and ''[[La casa de las sombras]]'' (1976).\n\nShe continued to appear on stage, notably in ''Dames at Sea'', ''Barefoot in the Park'' and ''The Sound of Music''.\n\nShe was seen on ''[[Satan's Cheerleaders]]'' (1977), ''[[Nocturna (1979 film)|Nocturna]]'' (1979), ''[[Guyana: Cult of the Damned]]'' (1979), ''[[Fuego negro]]'' (1979), ''[[The Silent Scream (1979 film)|The Silent Scream]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Man with Bogart's Face ]]'' (1980). She guest starred on shows like ''[[Fantasy Island]]''.\n\nDe Carlo was in ''[[The Munsters' Revenge]]'' (1981), then ''[[Liar's Moon]]'' (1982), ''[[Play Dead (1981 film)|Play Dead]]'' (1982), ''Vultures'' (1984), ''[[Flesh and Bullets]]'' (1985), and ''[[A Masterpiece of Murder]]'' (1986) (with [[Bob Hope]]). She was in a revival of ''The Munsters''.\n\nDe Carlo's later films included ''[[American Gothic (1988 film)|American Gothic]]'' (1988), for which she won the Best Actress Award from [[Fantafestival|International Science Fiction and Fantasy Film Show (Fantafestival)]]; ''[[Cellar Dweller]]'' (1988); and ''[[Mirror, Mirror (1990 film)|Mirror Mirror]]'' (1990). She had a supporting role as the title character's Aunt Rosa in the [[Sylvester Stallone]] comedy ''[[Oscar (1991 film)|Oscar]]'' (1991). Aunt Rosa is present when Oscar's father, played by [[Kirk Douglas]], extracts \"a deathbed promise\" from his son. Of her role, De Carlo said, \"Mine is a small part&mdash;but funny.\"<ref name=\"In Search of ... Yvonne De Carlo\">{{cite news|last1=Broeske|first1=Pat H.|title=In Search of ... Yvonne De Carlo|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/entertainment/ca-155_1_carlo-yvonne-tv|accessdate=January 22, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 13, 1991}}</ref>\n\nShe was in ''[[The Naked Truth (1992 film)|The Naked Truth]]'' (1992), ''[[Seasons of the Heart (1993 film)|Seasons of the Heart]]'' (1993), and \"Death of Some Salesmen\" in ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'' (1993). She had a small cameo role in ''[[Here Come the Munsters]]'', a 1995 television film remake of ''The Munsters''. De Carlo, along with [[Al Lewis (actor)|Al Lewis]], [[Pat Priest (actress)|Pat Priest]], and [[Butch Patrick]], did not have to wear costumes \"because the Munsters have several lives.\"<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\">{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Susan|title=No Monkey Business : YVONNE DE CARLO TAKES ON ABC'S REMAKE OF 'THE BAREFOOT EXECUTIVE'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-05/news/tv-64921_1_barefoot-executive|accessdate=March 31, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 5, 1995}}</ref>\n\nHer final performance was as Norma, \"an eccentric [[Norma Desmond]] lookalike,\" in the 1995 television film ''[[The Barefoot Executive]]'', a [[Disney Channel]] remake of the [[The Barefoot Executive|1971 film of the same title]].<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\" /> Norma, a former [[stand-in]] for film actors, \"monkey-sits\" the title character, a chimpanzee named Archie who is able to predict top-rated television series. \"She has these outrageous costumes&mdash;six of them&mdash;and it's just a small part,\" De Carlo told ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. \"But I like to do small things now.\"<ref name=\"1995 Los Angeles Times article\" />\n\nIn 2007, her son Bruce revealed that, before her death, she played supporting roles in two independent films that have yet to be released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spiegelman|first1=Arthur|title=\"Munsters\" actress Yvonne De Carlo dies at 84|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-decarlo/munsters-actress-yvonne-de-carlo-dies-at-84-idUSN1030669220070111|accessdate=March 31, 2018|work=[[Reuters]]|date=January 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1950, De Carlo purchased an eleven-room ranch house on five-and-a-half acres of \"hilly woodland\" on [[Coldwater Canyon Avenue|Coldwater Canyon Drive]]{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=151}} in [[Studio City, Los Angeles]], above [[Beverly Hills]]. De Carlo described it as her \"dream home\" and hired an architect to help her design \"an English-style dining room, with paneling and stained-glass windows.\" She also built stables for her horses{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} and a large swimming pool.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carrol|first1=Lee|title=Shirley Temple ambitious for daughter|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/51595749?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+beverly+hills|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]|date=June 10, 1950}}</ref> She sold the property in 1975.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beale|first1=Lauren|title=Yvonne de Carlo's old compound in Studio City is listed|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/08/home/la-hm-hotprop-yvonne-de-carlo-20110208|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, she moved to a ranch in the [[Santa Ynez Valley]],{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=239}} near [[Solvang]], [[California]].\n\n===Relationships===\nDe Carlo's name was linked with a number of famous men through her career, including [[Howard Hughes]]<ref name=\"NYTobit\" /> and [[Robert Stack]]. It is claimed that she had affairs with [[Mohammad Reza Shah]] of Iran during the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=KINZER |first1=STEPHEN |title=All the Shah's men : an American coup and the roots of Middle East terror |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |isbn=0-471-26517-9 |page=62 |accessdate=|date=2003-06-27 }}</ref>. In 1947, she announced her engagement to actor [[Howard Duff]],<ref>\"Screen Lovers to Be Married\" ''Los Angeles Times,'' April 30, 1947, pg. 7.</ref> her co-star in ''Brute Force'' (1947) and ''Calamity Jane and Sam Bass'' (1949),  but they never married. She was engaged three more times&mdash;to American stuntman [[Jock Mahoney]], English photographer [[Cornel Lucas]], and Scottish actor [[Robert Urquhart (actor)|Richard Urquhart]]&mdash;but felt \"trapped\" whenever she looked at the engagement ring on her finger.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=93}} While engaged to Mahoney, De Carlo became pregnant and also discovered she had a large [[ovarian cyst]]. The tumor was surgically removed and, as a result, she lost the baby.{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=144}} Her relationship with Mahoney ended when De Carlo found out he was seeing another woman, actress [[Margaret Field]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=152}}\n\nIn 1954, she told a journalist:\n\n<blockquote>I think it is wonderful to work. I dedicate more time now than ever to study. I really like to delve deeply into the characters and the stories in order to make the most of each part I play. It seems best to remain free of any serious romantic attachments under these circumstances. I will have to meet an exceptional and understanding person, indeed, before I think of marriage. I haven't met such a person yet.<ref name=\"edwin\"/></blockquote>\n\n===Marriage===\n[[File:Yvonne De Carlo and Bob Morgan at the New York premiere of The Ten Commandments.JPG|thumb|De Carlo with her husband, Robert Morgan, at the New York premiere of ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)]]\nDe Carlo met [[stunt performer|stuntman]] Robert Drew \"Bob\" Morgan (1915\u20131999) on the set of ''Shotgun'' in 1955, but he was married and had a child, daughter Bari Lee (b. 1947),<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~houghtonfamily/Morgan/p12.htm Profile], genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com; accessed June 21, 2016.</ref> and De Carlo had \"no intention of causing that marriage to break up.\"{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=134}} However, they met again, after the death of Morgan's wife, on the set of ''The Ten Commandments'' in Egypt,<ref name=\"She's A Happy Homebody! Marriage, Motherhood Curb Yvonne's Urge to Travel\">{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|authorlink1=Hedda Hopper|title=She's A Happy Homebody! Marriage, Motherhood Curb Yvonne's Urge to Travel|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1956/12/30/page/124/article/shes-a-happy-homebody|accessdate=January 5, 2017|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=December 30, 1956}}</ref> where they \"seemed immediately attracted to each other.\"{{sfn|Foster|2003|p=135}} They were married on November 21, 1955, at St. Stephen's Episcopal Church in [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref name=\"Most Glamorous Spinster Loses Title in Reno; Hollywood Actress Weds in Quiet Ceremony\">{{cite news|title=Most Glamorous Spinster Loses Title in Reno; Hollywood Actress Weds in Quiet Ceremony|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/79190405/|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=Nevada State Journal|date=November 22, 1955}}</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,893252,00.html Profile], ''Time Magazine''; accessed June 21, 2016.</ref> De Carlo raised Bari as her own and had two sons with Morgan: Bruce Ross (b. 1956), whose godfather was [[Cecil B. DeMille]];{{sfn|Orrison|1999|p=113}}{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=84}} and Michael (1957\u20131997).\n\nMorgan lost his left leg after being run over by a train while filming ''[[How the West Was Won (film)|How the West Was Won]]'' (1962). However, his contract with [[MGM]] assumed no responsibility for the accident. De Carlo and Morgan filed a $1.4 million lawsuit against the studio, claiming her husband was permanently disabled. They divorced in July 1973.<ref name=\"California Divorce Index\">{{cite web|title=Peggy Y Middleton - California Divorce Index|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPRV-DPC|website=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nDe Carlo, a [[United States nationality law|naturalized citizen]] of the United States, was an active [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] who campaigned for [[Richard Nixon]],<ref name=\"Yvonne DeCarlo A Star Reborn\">{{cite news|last1=Christy|first1=Marian|title=Yvonne DeCarlo A Star Reborn|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19720712&id=7JMjAAAAIBAJ&pg=6095,798572&hl=en|accessdate=August 18, 2015|work=[[Reading Eagle]]|agency=United Feature Syndicate|date=July 12, 1972}}</ref> [[Ronald Reagan]]<ref>\"Southland Observations: There's No Business Like Politics\" Kerby, Phil. ''Los Angeles Times'', August 12, 1976, pg. D1.</ref> and [[Gerald Ford]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schwartzenberg|first1=Roger-G\u00e9rard|title=The Superstar Show of Government|date=1980|publisher=[[Barron's Educational Series]]|isbn=9780812052589|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f_ocAAAAIAAJ&dq=yvonne+de+carlo+supporter+gerald+ford&q=Yvonne+de+Carlo|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[Conservatism|conservative]], she stated half-jokingly in a 1976 television interview: \"I'm all for men and I think they ought to stay up there and be the bosses, and have women wait on them hand and foot and put their slippers on and hand them the pipe and serve seven course meals; as long as they open the door, support the woman, and do their duty in the bedroom, et cetera.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo on feminism, equal rights & Hollywood, 1976|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p9vDKRQMk5s|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nDe Carlo's maternal grandparents came from distinct religious backgrounds: He was [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and she was [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=19}} They raised her as an [[Anglican]]; she was a member and chorister of Vancouver's [[St. Paul's Anglican Church (Vancouver)|St. Paul's Anglican Church]].{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=122}}\n\nIn her autobiography, De Carlo wrote about her faith in God: \"God has saved me and mine from some pretty sticky situations. For me, religion is a little like being a Republican or a Democrat. It's not the party that counts, it's the man. Therefore, I care not what house of worship I enter, be it Catholic, Presbyterian, or Baptist. I elected God a long time ago and I'll stick with Him, because I don't think His term will ever be up.\"{{sfn|De Carlo|Warren|1987|p=239}}\n\n==Death==\nDe Carlo suffered a minor [[stroke]] in 1998. She later became a resident of the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]], in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]], where she spent her last years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/11/arts/television/11decarlo.html|title=Yvonne De Carlo - The Munsters - Obituary|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=2007-01-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She died from [[heart failure]] on January 8, 2007, and was cremated.<ref name=NYTobit>{{cite news|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|title=Yvonne De Carlo Dies at 84; Played Lily on 'Munsters'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/11/arts/television/11decarlo.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 25, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 11, 2007|page=B6}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* In 1946, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named her one of the three \"top new Hollywood stars\" of 1945, along with [[Lizabeth Scott]] and [[Lauren Bacall]]: \"Miss de Carlo is definitely a personality. She has proved this in Universal's ''Salome, Where She Danced'', and followed this appearance as star in [the] same company's ''Frontier Gal''. She is a controversial figure, but she's managed to come out a star during discussions.\"<ref name=\"Lizabeth Scott, Bacall, de Carlo Top New Hollywood Stars A-Blooming\">{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Whitney|title=Lizabeth Scott, Bacall, de Carlo Top New Hollywood Stars A-Blooming|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 9, 1946|volume=161|issue=5|pages=3, 68|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety161-1946-01#page/n49/mode/2up/search/de+carlo|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* She was a medalist in ''[[Boxoffice (magazine)|Boxoffice Barometer]]'''s The All-American Screen Favorites of 1946 list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The All-American Screen Favorites of 1946|journal=Boxoffice Barometer|date=November 9, 1946|page=18\u2013A|url=https://archive.org/stream/boxofficebaromet00boxo_3#page/n17/mode/2up/search/yvonne|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* She was a medalist in ''Boxoffice Barometer'''s The All-American Screen Favorites of 1947 list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The All-American Screen Favorites of 1947|journal=Boxoffice Barometer|date=November 15, 1947|page=19|url=https://archive.org/stream/boxofficebaromet00boxo_4#page/n17/mode/2up/search/yvonne+de+carlo|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* In 1947, [[Max Factor]]'s chief hair stylist, Fred Fredericks, named her one of the 10 \"best tressed\" film actresses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gives 'Best Tressed' Film Stars|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/127077723?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+tressed|accessdate=April 5, 2018|work=News|date=January 22, 1947}}</ref>\n* In 1950, the Camera Club of America voted her \"Sexnicolor Queen of the Screen\" \"for putting more sex [appeal] into [[Technicolor]] than any other star.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM BRIEFS - Queen Yvonne|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18487164?searchTerm=yvonne+de+carlo+queen+technicolor|accessdate=April 5, 2018|work=[[The Sun-Herald|The Sunday Herald]]|date=December 10, 1950}}</ref>\n* In 1957, she received a BoxOffice Blue Ribbon Award for ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956).<ref name=\"Boxoffice Blue Ribbon Awards\">{{cite web|title=Recipients of Two or More Awards From March 1932, Through August 1965 Are Herein Cited|url=http://www.astortheater.org/articles20.html|website=Astor Theater|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* In 1960, she was awarded two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. The motion picture star is on the south side of the 6100 block of Hollywood Boulevard. The television star is on the north side of the 6700 block of Hollywood Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo - Hollywood Star Walk - Los Angeles Times|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/yvonne-de-carlo/|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* In 1964, she received a second BoxOffice Blue Ribbon Award for ''[[McLintock!]]'' (1963).<ref name=\"Boxoffice Blue Ribbon Awards\" />\n* In 1966, she was honored by the [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|City of Niagara Falls, Canada]], for \"having created good will for her native country and given inspiration to others.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In Hollywood - Yvonne Honored|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=DS19660521.2.31&txq=yvonne+de+carlo+honored|accessdate=April 6, 2018|work=[[The Desert Sun|Desert Sun]]|agency=UPI|date=May 21, 1966}}</ref>\n* In 1966, she was named honorary mayor of [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Monstrous Mayor\" />\n* In 1987, she won the [[Fantafestival|International Science Fiction and Fantasy Film Show (Fantafestival) Award]] for Best Actress for ''[[American Gothic (1988 film)|American Gothic]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grazzini|first1=Giovanni|title=Cinema|date=1987|publisher=Ed. Laterza|isbn=9788842030300|page=213}}</ref>\n* In 2005, she was one of the 250 female Hollywood legends nominated for the [[American Film Institute]]'s [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Stars|100 Years ... 100 Stars]] list.<ref>{{cite web |title=America's Greatest Legends \u2013 A compendium of the 500 stars nominated for top 50 \"Greatest Screen Legends\" status. |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100years/stars500.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2007, she was nominated for the \"Who Knew They Could Sing?\" [[TV Land Award]] for ''[[The Munsters]]''.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In the 1954 ''[[I Love Lucy]]'' episode \"Ricky's Screen Test\", Lucy reads in a newspaper that MGM is considering several Hollywood actresses, including Yvonne De Carlo, for the female lead role in Ricky's film ''Don Juan''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Monush |first1=Barry |last2=Sheridan |first2=James |title=Lucille Ball FAQ: Everything Left to Know About America's Favorite Redhead |date=2011 |publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vq2Zff8JZZ8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9781557839336 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Yvonne De Carlo filmography}}\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles===\n* \"I Love a Man\" / \"Say Goodbye\" ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]], 1950)<ref>{{cite web|title=78 RPM - Yvonne De Carlo - Say Goodbye / I Love A Man - Columbia - UK - DB.2850|url=http://www.45worlds.com/78rpm/record/db2850|website=45worlds|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"Take It Or Leave It\" / \"Three Little Stars\" ([[Capitol Records|Capitol]], 1955)<ref>{{cite web|title=Yvonne De Carlo - Take It Or Leave It / Three Little Stars - Capitol - USA - F3206|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/f3206|website=45cat|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"That's Love\" / \"The Secret of Love\" ([[Imperial Records|Imperial]], 1957)<ref name=\"Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'\">{{cite web|title=Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'|url=http://honkingduck.com/discography/artist/yvonne_de_carlo|website=The Honking Duck|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"I Would Give My Heart\" / \"Rockin' In The Orbit\" (Imperial, 1958)<ref name=\"Recordings by 'Yvonne De Carlo'\" />\n\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Yvonne De Carlo Sings]]'' (Masterseal, 1957)\n\n===Duets===\n* \"[[You Belong to My Heart]]\" with [[Bill Lee (singer)|Bill Lee]] (included in ''That's Entertainment! The Ultimate Anthology of M-G-M Musicals'')<ref>{{cite web|title=That's Entertainment! The Ultimate Anthology of M-G-M Musicals [Rhino Box Set]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thats-entertainment%21-the-ultimate-anthology-of-m-g-m-musicals-rhino-box-set-mw0000723726|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n* \"[[Getting to Know You (song)|Getting to Know You]]\" with [[Frank Sinatra]] (included in ''The Frank Sinatra Duets'')<ref>{{cite web|title=The Frank Sinatra Duets|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/comp/frank-sinatra/the-frank-sinatra-duets-1/|website=[[Rate Your Music]]|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Bawden|first1=James|last2=Miller|first2=Ron|chapter=Yvonne De Carlo|title=You Ain't Heard Nothin' Yet: Interviews with Stars from Hollywood's Golden Era|year=2017|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|isbn=9780813174235|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=De Carlo|first1=Yvonne|last2=Warren|first2=Doug|title=Yvonne: An Autobiography|year=1987|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|isbn=9780312002176|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/yvonneautobiogra00deca_0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foster|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Foster (writer)|chapter=Yvonne De Carlo|title=Once Upon a Time in Paradise: Canadians in the Golden Age of Hollywood|year=2003|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|isbn=9781459712676|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Orrison|first=Katherine|authorlink=Katherine Orrison|chapter=Mrs. Moses: Yvonne De Carlo|title=Written in Stone: Making Cecil B. DeMille's Epic The Ten Commandments|year=1999|publisher=Vestal Press|isbn=9781461734819|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nick|chapter=Bruce Morgan on Yvonne De Carlo|title=Raised by the Stars: Interviews with 29 Children of Hollywood Actors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yImkNboc4tsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2011|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|isbn=978-0-7864-6403-6|ref